    'from' => 'Stefan Matthias Aust sma@kiel.netsurf.de',
    'body' => '>This piece was created as foundation description of Traveller, its features
>and benefits. Constructive criticism is sincerely invited.

The text summarises some well known facts and it sounds good.

>TECHNOLOGICAL SCIENCE PROVIDES A FOUNDATION

We also see the reappearance of reactionless maneuver drives, fine. Will
Gravitiy manipulation also be used to build something like force screens?
The other missing answer is on the role of computer technology. What is its
technological and sociological importance? Will computers stay as slow, big,
monolithic calculation engines of the seventies or will they reappear as
more up to date multi-purpose tools? What\'s about robots or AIs?

>SOCIAL SCIENCE ADDS CHARACTER AND FLAVOR

The position of robots in society has also important effects on sociology. I
hope the beginning Imperium is more pro-robot (as for example the society
shown by the star wars movies where (the non-intelligent) robots where just
another tool very common for all people and in contrast to the post-virus
TNE society that feared everything more complicated than a pocket watch). On
the cosmopolitan universe: My view of the Imperium was always tolerance,
tolerance up to indifference about all kind of governments. Keep it so! But
don\'t see capitalism as the only working form of society. They Imperium
might follow this ideology (because it works so well :-) but there should
always be exceptions.

>ADVENTURE!
>[...] combat, travel, tasks. 

I strongly hope, Traveller isn\'t a combat centric game. IMHO MT and TNE lost
much because their orientation toward military missions. Something like

...travel, exploration, combat, negoation and all kinds of task.

as adventure concept I would like much better!

>HISTORY OF THE UNIVERSE

>[...] Ziru Sirka, with 40,000 worlds.

Huh, the number I remebered (and was used in TNE) was about 11.000 worlds.
Has the empire grown or do they now count different? TNE shown sligthly
different dates (4518 instead of 4521 for example) but that seems
unimportant. Interestingly, this text didn\'t mention the virus, perhaps... :-)

>THERE\'S MORE!

I like this summary of Traveller, mainly because I always liked the overall
setting and had most problems only with rules and given technology (mainly
the design systems) and the main emphasis of (MT and) TNE to military
adventures (starting with rules like TNE that ease combat up to the whole
concept of the RC which was \'if another world is too weak to protect their
wealth one could go and take it)\'.

One point, that came to my mind is the world design. Will it be the same
system as used since the beginning (for the snake of backward
compartibility) or something better. Rolling up some worlds is fun (and more
than inventing vehicles IMHO) but the current system gives some very strange
results because population is independ of all other values. It\'s also
strange that each system always has exactly one mainworld.

bye
