    'body' => 'Greetings All:

Im (still) in the midst of preparing for a new Traveller campaign (Im
leaning towards the Classic setting, but might hold off until the first T4
items come out to see if well switch there). Ive been going through things
that look odd since the original incarnation of Traveller to todays
technology. Of course, one of the biggest glaring differences are in the way
Traveller portrayed computers vs. what we have today (and this difference
is, as we all know, one of the longest sources of debate starting from the
Origins seminars I attended way back when to todays discussions on how T4
will look!).

Ive thought of a few things to present to my players and would like to run
them past you and your collective wisdom.

Reason One for difference: Traveller was written in the mid-1970s. We
werent wired then they way we are now and nobody really thought wed advance
as quickly. So it has a sort of clunky anachronistic charm. I feel
uncomfortable changing the rules because its like picking at a loose thread
on your suit: You might end up unraveling the whole thing.

Reason Two for difference: Most of the ships in the Traveller universe are
built for rough travel. Its a jungle out there: Unfriendly powers, pirates,
troublesome natives. You never know when youre going to run into a storm
while re-fueling around a gas giant, or a bubble in hyperspace. The computers
are built military style--ultra-rough and tough to take a lot of punishment.

Reason Three for difference: Many years ago, humaniti had much better
computers. Heck, they even developed computers that would think for
themselves and had psionic powers! Then some of these telepathic AIs tried
to take things over. That was the start of the Psionic Suppressions--and of
course, as you know, things didnt end there. Thats way today (the Classic
era) we have psionic powers suppressed and computers are clunky--nobody
really trusts either and they only build computers advanced enough to do the
job and no better.

Waiting your counter-battery bursts...

Fred Kiesche
(FKiesche3@aol.com)

