    'from' => 'FKiesche3@aol.com',
    'body' => 'Greetings:

Gads--what sugary memories that subject brings back!

Anyway: How do you all handle the passage of time in your campaigns? We have
the standard Imperial Year, Day, Hour, Minute, Second, etc. I presume that
most ships, especially Imperial Military ships follow Imperial time. But what
about smaller ships? Independent ships?

And--does anybody ever use odd days in their campaign. You land on the
planet--the day is 12 standard hours long--or 48?

I\'ve recently come across a few pieces of SF that had interesting treatments
of this idea.

The first is CJ Cherryh\'s "Downbelow Station". Orbiting Pell, a planet around
Tau Ceti, Downbelow Station has taken on Pell\'s day, which is longer (by
nearly twice, if my memory is correct) than that of Earth. To compensate, the
station (and the ground contingent) operate on the "Main Day" and "Alter Day"
schedule--the two together make up one Pell Day.

The second is David Weber\'s "Honor Harrington" series. I\'m slogging through
the first of the series "On Basilisk Station". One thing that was amusing was
the first chapter, where galactic directions are given as North, South, East
and West. Apparently this universe is as flat as the Traveller Universe
(insert big grin and wink here). The "pocket empire" where the action takes
place has a number of differing days and years for each planet in the system.
As a result, computers have a time calculator built in and the author
mentions on more than one occasion the differences between the times of each
planet. For example, one planet has a fairly normal day of hours (60 minutes
each), plus one additional shorter hour to compensate for the
difference--this additional hour being called a "comp".

Kim Stanley Robinson and Philip K. Dick use a similar approach for Mars. P.K.
Dick coined the term "The Martian Time Slip" for the difference between a
Terran day and a Martian day. Robinson follows up on this and has the clocks
of his Martian colony flash "24:00" until the end of the time slip. I recall
that in "The Rolling Stones", Robert A. Heinlein had one of the twin
characters (Castor and Pollux, of course!) leave his watch on Terran time,
