Knowledge is one thing but access to the necessary tools and equipment is
another.  For example, I know the basic theories behind casting a cast-iron
engine block... now all I need is the smelting plant, a forge, and a mold of the
original  8-)

If such a skill allows maintenance of such equipment, it would be extremely
*specialized* knowledge.  Repair of high tech equipment is no longer "repair"
but "Re & Re" or simply "replacement" of damaged components (Ford just came out
with a non-servicable transmission).  Even today, companies don\'t spend a lot of
time repairing items such as PCs; they replace entire components instead.  Under
battlefield conditions, you have to decide how many seperate components make up
a single suit of Battle Dress and if all of these components are kept in stock
at the local depot at all times.

Personally, I\'ve always considered repair-type skills to be entirely different
than building- & design-type skills.  IMHO, one requires a natural-born
mechanical aptitude while the other requires an education in engineering,
architecture, etc.
