    'topic' => 'Religion - a skill?',
    'month' => '06',
    'index' => 'ad821',
    'body' => 'I think the question of religion skill raises an important point: do 
skills define a character\'s origin, or does the character define what and 
why the skills are? In other words, does a character become `religious\' 
or knowledgeable about religion (a) because she has that skill or (b) 
because that is a background which explains (some of) the skills that 
character has?

Taking me as an example, under model (a) I would have a UPP something like

664BC8 Scientist, in 2nd term, age 24 Cr few
Religion-2 Chemistry-2 Physics-1 Computing-1 Instruction-1 Jack-o-T-1

Under model (b) I would be more like

664BC8 Scientist, in 2nd term, age 24 Cr few
Chemistry-2 Physics-1 Computing-1 Instruction-1 Liason-1 Psychology-1 JoT-1

with the Liason skill representing learning to get along with people in a 
practical sense and the Psychology being something in which I\'m interested,
partly in the context of understanding people\'s spirituality.

The point I\'m trying to make is that skills in Traveller represent 
specific things that a character can do well, and which are likely to be 
used quite often. We could get silly with the skills above, and start 
including ones like Guitar-1 and Technical Writing-2, but these skills 
are simply not necessary; if it becomes particularly important that a 
character\'s guitar playing be impressive, then the ref can assign a level 
of skill based on how much time the character practices, and roll a task 
based on skill and Dex (say). Technical writing is a function of 
education and technical competence (appropriate science skill).

Going back to religion, therefore, I would separate this out into 
`generally applicable skills\' (social and academic, mainly) and `things 
in which the character takes a particular interest\' (which I would 
moderate via rolls on Edu, Int and maybe Soc, or -- mostly -- via role 
playing). The former should be part of the main skill set; the latter are 
characterisations and part of the role-playing proper.

Mind you, having said all that, you do need to have a reasonable number 
of `basic\' skills. I wouldn\'t go back to the CT `scientists have computer 
skill and maybe electronics\' approach...

Nick

