Planetary), or (Trade, Criminal, ...).  Of course, I\'m a law student, so 
when I look at it I see it as a big, diverse, field.


>Medicine (DM) (DH) [I like the idea of Med-1 being 1st Aid up to Med-4
>being surgeon].

I have issues with it.  There are a lot of paths to explore in medicine 
besides surgery.  I have a feeling that the "Med-4 = surgeon" thing is a 
consequence of the emphasis on military things.  There should be people 
with Med-6 who are experts in, say, communicable diseases (this is 
especially relevant when you\'re exploring new planets!).  Most real-world 
physicians do not perform surgery, and have only been exposed to it 
during clinical rotations.

****
XENOQUALIFIERS

Certain skills are going to exist in different versions where different 
races (and sometimes cultures) are concerned.  Both of the skills above 
are good examples.  An Imperial Naval physician with Med-5 who has to 
treat a Vargr will (unless she\'s served with a Vargr unit) not be 
operating anywhere near level 5, and if she has to treat a K\'Kree may be 
no better than someone who has taken a first aid course.  Similarly, a 
lawyer from Vland called in to argue a case on, say, Lair would be 
shocked at what constitutes appropriate courtroom conduct and would 
almost certainly hose his client badly.

Other obvious skills include (off the top of my head) Streetwise, 
Bribery, Liaison, Leadership, *possibly* Broker and Trader (though the 
trade community might be cosmopolitan enough that it wouldn\'t matter), 
Interview, Interrogation.  There are probably others.

I can think of three ways to handle this:

1.  Ignore the differences (I think this is foolish, and tends to make the
    aliens more like "humans in funny suits")

2.  Allow characters who spend time around a different culture or race,
    using their skill, to receive a "xenoqualifier" attached to it, thus
    letting them use the skill effectively in that context

3.  Allow characters to purchase the xenoqualified versions of a skill
    separately from the Imperium versions

I use a combination of (2) and (3) in my own campaign.  I use 2, for 
example, with Medical skill, making -- perhaps wrongly -- the assumption 
that some of the skills learned in human medicine carry over.  I use 3 
with "interaction" skills like Streetwise, where the behavior patterns 
are so culture-dependent that you really need a new skill.

This has come up in my game because the PCs misjumped way deep into Vargr 
space, and have been learning the ropes.

Comments?  Criticisms?  Flames^H^H^H^H^H^HHarsh Criticisms?

Joe Saul
jmsaul@umich.edu
