    'body' => ' ::>Subject: (LONG) Chuck\'s New And Improved Skill List

 ::>NOTE ON SKILLS BY TECH LEVEL

 ::>I think skills should be understood to be mediated by the character\'s
 ::>native TL.  Someone from a TL-5 world might have mechanic skill, but he
 ::>won\'t be able to repair starship turrets (At least not  easily.  I\'d say
 ::>give a -DM equal to the TL difference).

 My gut inclination is to complicate this a little bit:  If the
 _concept_ being addressed exists at the lower TL, your rule (DM
 -TLDiff) applies; if it doesn\'t, the task becomes impossible (not
 Impossible the success level, impossible as in "you can\'t do it.")

 Example:  Gasoline-fueled internal-combustion become available in
 the form of the Model-T at TL(4? 5?).  They are still common
 technology (in the form of the Porsche 911) at TL8.  Henry Ford I,
 who could repair one of his own machines, would be able to at
 least understand in principle what\'s going on in that Porsche, but
 couldn\'t repair it as well as he could one of his own.

 Leonardo daVinci, genius as he was, had no conception of the IC
 engine.  You could explain it to him (in Italian, with lots of
 circumlocutions for missing vocabulary), and he might very well
 understand it, but without learning the technology, he\'d not have
 a prayer of being able to do anything with it, in spite of being
 a good mechanic by the standards of his time.


 ::>SKILL CATEGORIES

 ::>(D) Default: represents a skill that everyone has at level-0.
 ::> (DL): only individuals at low (3-) tech levels get this as default.
 ::> (DM): only individuals at medium TL (4-8) get this as default.
 ::> (DH): only individuals at high TL (9+) get this as default.
 ::>[I considered having Dn+, where n would be a specific tech level, but I
 ::>think this is simpler and does the job just as well. Comments?]

 Unless you\'re going to allow default modification based on other
 than TL (and I think you should), drop the distinction, and don\'t
 provide default skills that are TL-specific.  If you do go with
 other-factor defaults, it\'s better to just list the minimum
 criteria that must be met for it to be a default skill:

 Swimming (D Hyd=9+)

 Any character that lives on a world that\'s more than 85% water
 covered will know how to swim.

 Watercraft, motorized (D Hyd=9+, TL6+)

 Anyone that lives on a world that\'s more than 85% water covered,
 and which has a tech level sufficient for mass-produced motor
 boats will know how to operate a motorboat.

 Watercraft, human powered (D Hyd=9+)

 Any character that lives on a world that\'s more than 85% water
 covered will know how to build rafts, and probably rowboats or
 canoes as well.

 Vacc Suit (D Atm=3-, TL=8+)

 Anyone that lives on a world with a normally-unbreathably-thin
 atmosphere, with a technology high enough to build space suits,
 will know how to wear one, and conduct routine activities in it.

 ::>(C) Cascade: represents a group of related skills.  Pick one of them and
 ::>all others are at 1/2 level.

 ::>(G) Group:  represents a group of related skills.  Pick one of them but
 ::>get level-nil in all others (or level-0 at GM\'s discretion).

 My gut feeling is that with proper grouping of skill groups, it
 would be more appropriate to say level-1 if the primary is at
 level-3 or better, level-0 otherwise.



 ::>***MILITARY SKILLS*************************

 ::>Archery (C) [I do not think this should be a default skill]
 ::> -Bow
 ::> -Crossbow
 ::> -Sling
 ::> -Atlatl

 I have no idea of what an atlatl is, but Crossbow is probably more
 akin to your Ranged Weapon than to the others listed here.  And
 bow (as in conventional, not cross) is far different from sling.
 Toss this group, or convert it to Archaic Weapons (Group,
 level-nil) and add cudgel/mace/axe/hammer, blade, and polearm.  If
 you go with the latter, copy Crossbow into the Ranged Weapon
 group.

 ::>Blade (C)
 ::> -Short Blade (D): knives, daggers, blades...
 ::> -Long Blade (D) : swords, cutlass, broadsword...
 ::> -2 Hand Blade (D): bastard sword, 2 handed sword...

 Keep this as a cascade, but make it a choice off the Archaic
 Weapons group.  Bastard Sword should be in both Long and 2-Hand.

 ::>Cudgel (C)
 ::> -Short Club (D) : billy club, bo stick, bottle...
 ::> -Long Club (D) : baseball bat, treebranch...
 ::> -Staff (D) : staff, pole, broomhandle...

 I\'d make Hammer/Mace part of this cluster, possibly as additional
 weapons in Long.  I\'m not sure where to put Axe.

 ::>Environment Combat (C)
 ::> -Low gravity
 ::> -High gravity
 ::> -Jungle
 ::> -Desert
 ::> etc. etc.

 Definitely etc.  Including Urban.

