 ::> -Short HAM (D) : ballpeen hammer, hatchet...
 ::> -Long HAM (D) : warhammer, mace...
 ::> -2 Hand HAM (D): battleaxe, woodaxe, 2H mace....

 See above, Cudgel.

 ::>Laser Weapon (C)
 ::> -Pistol (DH)
 ::> -Rifle (DH)

 Carbine?

 ::>Melee Weapon (G) (see individual skills for cascade options)
 ::> -Blade (C)
 ::> -Cudgel (C)
 ::> -Hammer/Axe/Mace (C)
 ::> -Throw

 Aha!  Here\'s where Sling should be - part of Throw, which I would
 assert should include rocks, spears, etc.

 ::>Ranged Weapon (G) (see individual skills for cascade options)
 ::> -Slug Weapon (C)
 ::> -Laser Weapon (C)
 ::> -Energy Weapons
 ::> -Heavy Weapon (C)
 ::> -Sonic Weapon (C)

 Crossbow, here.  As well in Archaic.

 ::>Slug Weapon (C)  [Each includes tranq, googun, and tangler equivalents.]
 ::> -Pistol (DM) (DH)
 ::> -Rifle (DM) (DH)
 ::> -Shotgun (DM) (DH)
 ::> -SMG  [I don\'t think any autoweapons should be default]
 ::> -Autorifle [includes gauss weapons at TL 9+]

 Carbine?

 ::>Unarmed Combat (D)
 ::>[I don\'t like the idea of distinguishing Brawling and Martial Arts.  Yes
 ::>they are different, but they aim to achieve the same goal and have the
 ::>same results. I would lump both into this skill.]

 Yes, and no.  I\'ve heard it asserted that Brawling-equivalent
 skills are for beating the stuffing out of the opponent, relying
 on overpowering force.  Martial arts are for using the opponent\'s
 skill against him.

 The eight-year-old isn\'t going to have a prayer against the
 professional boxer in straight brawling-equivalent, but if the 8yo
 can get the leverage (not impossible), he _can_ discourage the
 boxer.  Separate \'em out, but use selection of a specific
 martial-arts style strictly as a "color" item.

 Brawling-equivalent is a STR/END skill.  Martial Arts is a DEX
 skill.



