    'body' => 'On Sun, 9 Jun 1996 That Computer Guy <darkstar@udel.edu> wrote:

[Me:]

> : Taking me as an example, under model (a) I would have a UPP something like
> : 
> : 664BC8 Scientist, in 2nd term, age 24 Cr few
> : Religion-2 Chemistry-2 Physics-1 Computing-1 Instruction-1 Jack-o-T-1
> : 
> : Under model (b) I would be more like
> : 
> : 664BC8 Scientist, in 2nd term, age 24 Cr few
> : Chemistry-2 Physics-1 Computing-1 Instruction-1 Liason-1 Psychology-1 JoT-1
> 
> But the problem here is that it doesn\'t take into account Religious
> studies.  You\'ve gone from being a religious academic in the first
> example to a ship\'s counselor in the second.

With respect, no. What I\'m saying is that theological literacy and
`religious knowledge\' are a function of education and (maybe)
intelligence. The applicable, transferable skills gained from the practice
of religion are something else -- Fast Talk, Persuasion, Admin,
Streetwise, Psychology, even Science (in a technocratic religion) or
Forgery/Bribery (in a mercantile one, like that of Nedra in the Belgariad).
Rob Prior\'s complaint that people don\'t really take the 
intellectual side of things seriously -- or can\'t -- is something I would 
translate into game terms as: many people who profess a faith are in fact 
`only\' part of a culture. If the game is going to have Religion skill, you 
ought to have Vilani skill, 46 different Vargr skills... not entirely a 
facetious idea, incidentally.

Now, while I\'m sure I\'d rate at least Religion-1 (Christian), that is a
function of being relatively intelligent and over-educated; my ability to
debate things religious is a function of scientific training, background
knowledge etc.. In other words, religion is part of my educational
development and inseperable from it. This is why I\'d make PCs committed to
a religion make the occasional roll vs. Education, rather than inventing
another skill, or I\'d just invent the occasional task. (Maybe there should
be some suggestions about `rolls for casual knowledge\' e.g. they are
usually Difficult, Edu -- or Routine, Edu, Computer with the aid of a
suitable database -- and 1 difficulty lower if the character is
particularly knowledgeable, e.g. an ex-Navy officer on naval history.)

To go back to our Traveller example, if I were really well-informed about 
Christianity (debatable) then I wouldn\'t rate History or Sociology skill 
- -- it\'d be historical or sociological (or theological) `facts\' I knew.
If I were a trained theologian (I\'m not), I would probably have History or 
Sociology skill, because those would be *transferable* skills, methods of 
working and understanding concepts that can be used in other fields, 
wherever they were gained.


> A skill like "Religion"
> or even "Scholar (Religion)" should cover more than just confession.
> What about the 158 yr old Vilani archeologist who\'s been searching for
> the Holy Tea Set?  Surely he would have a Religion-3 which doesn\'t
