I\'ll admit it Dave.  I loved TNE.  I hated getting into starship combat because that 
pretty much wasted an afternoon.  But I loved the system, the rules were good, 
providing you didn\'t get hit with a propelled grenade then things got messy, combat 
was easy, the equipment was supurb etc, etc, etc.  I\'ll buy the new system and if I 
think I can apply any of the stuff to my campaign I will.  But I intend to continue 
battling the virus and re-opening the frontiers of civilization.

Inspite of everyone\'s bitching about FF&S I liked it too, it needed to be better layed 
out, but it was essentially an excelent system.  Once you\'d designed something once it 
became really easy after that.  The problem I found was everyone looked at the first 
page, got intimidated and said, I don\'t have time for this.  This was from the same 
people who would happly spent two hours detailing a system out to the last moon of the 
last ice ball.  I can whip together a rifle in under twenty minutes, I can put 
together a starship in under three hours, and I can design a grav tank down to the 
fusion cannon in less than two hours.  Everybody whines about the system but how many 
of them really sat down and tried it as opposed to looking at the tables and getting 
flustered.  There\'s an art to designing equipment, it\'s not just a bunch of numbers on 
a page.  It\'s a living breathing organizm.

"You run into an Imperial Grav Tank."

"What\'s it look like?"

"It\'s square with a turret on top."

"Sounds ugly.  You got a picture?"

"No."

"Can you sketch me a picture."

"No, I just cranked it out ten minutes ago."

There\'s more to designing equipment than just crunching the numbers.  Like I said it\'s 
art and don\'t let anybody else convince you other wise.  A gearhead can crank the 
numbers through, an artist knows what it looks like and makes the pictures and plans 
while doing the work so everyone else knows what it looks like.

Derek Stanley
