    'body' => 'On 11 Jun 96 at 11:00, That Computer Guy spewed:

> However, that isn\'t the case here.  Is your hate of TNE so great that
> you won\'t allow any of it to influence T4?  And how can you even
> compare IG to GDW.  If IG did like GDW and not listen to our input,
> then we\'d be looking at HG 2.  As it stands, lots of things have been
> reverse engineered, mechanics to match the story line, and ease of use
> has been incorporated.  You can now create ships as quickly as Books 2
> and 5 (and yes, this will be the initial stuff), and eventually all of
> us gearheads will be able to get off by designing every nook and
> cranny down to the damn glove compartment.
> 

Jerry, 

Well put, if somewhat blunt.  

I say this as somebody who has never designed a ship with FF&S, and 
has never played TNE (although I have the books for the system, and 
HAVE read them).  The facts are that a lot of people liked FF&S, and 
IMO it was probably the best thing that GDW designed out of the TNE 
stuff.  In my opinion, that\'s a bit like saying it\'s the best 
ballerina in Galveston, TX, but FF&S was a good idea.  I think that a 
tweaked FF&S under a different name in a year or two would be a fine 
addition to my collection.  There is a simpler design system, and we 
can thank IG in general and Don Perrin in particular for seeking 
input.  A simple system and a complex system should please everybody. 
 
It\'s time for the CT folks to face facts.  this is not 1977.  Most of 
the people on this list are veterans of 10-20 years of RPG 
experience.  My first RPG was Tunnels & Trolls.  A crude design, 
terrible mechanics, and no product support.  Would I play it again, 
now?  Not in a million years.  Would I use book 2 to fight starship 
combat or design starships?  Heck, I\'m not even sure I\'d want to use 
Book 5 again...  Again, not in a million years.  A large number of 
gamers feel the same way.  For you to bash FF&S just because you 
don\'t like it, is no better than what GDW did by assuming that 
everybody wanted to use a system as complex as FF&S.

The good news for the CT folks, is there\'s no Virus in the first 
mililieu, your campaigns will be writing the "canon", instead of 
being strangled by it.  The system is going to bear a closer 
resemblance to CT/MT than TNE, and IG is looking for ideas and 
input.  The strength of the game has always been the background first, 
and the rules second (or third), anyways.  

Stu
 
