    'month' => '06',
    'topic' => 'Why Traveller fizzled',
    'body' => '>I think this is more a function of the fact that the original 3 books
>didn\'t present the Imperium as THE game universe.  But hey, things

You seem to feel that the Imperium IS Traveller.  I\'ve always thought
that Traveller is a framework of rules on how to run a good Sci-Fi
game.  The official background is just that background.  

The rules should not attempt to explain technology, only present the
framework of how the technology is applied.  That way the GM is free
to create their own reasons without having to change major sections
of the base rule set.

If you say "If you don\'t like thruster plates, don\'t use them!", fine.
But if the rule set for space combat and ship design imply that MDrives
are thruster plates than I would have to change major parts of the rules.

>Oh pardon me if I get a tad offended by people who assume that if IG
>isn\'t reprinting the stuff from 20 years ago then the product will be
>crap.  Also, I find it hard to swallow that by making changes that

I\'m not saying that they need to reprint old material, but I am
suggesting that they print new material in the same way they did
20 years ago.  Specifically:

        Clearly separate the basic framework of rules from background.

and

        Keep the rules as simple as possible.

Somehow the Imperium seems to have became the only viable background.
No commercial products that I know of delt with alternate settings.
This I feel was one reason why Traveller fizzled.  Remember, TSR 
published several campaign settings for D&D.  

New players may have gotten the idea that Traveller was about 
Stephon, Zhodani and Aslans (or more recently Virus).  
And if they didn\'t like those things they wouldn\'t like Traveller.

- -Daniel



