    'body' => '>I think that the most likely candidate for drag is going to be the effect
>of the planet\'s atmosphere on the cable, but I don\'t have any figures for
>that, I\'m afraid.

I shouldn\'t have used the term "drag" - I meant it in the loose rather than
technical sense.  The cable isn\'t being pulled through the planet\'s
atmosphere, although I imagine that strong winds near the ground and
high-altitude jetstreams might have an effect on the structure.  Instead of
"drag" I should have said "pull": the weight of the cable is pulling the
asteroid down because although the asteroid is in free-fall, the cable is
not.  The cable is not in orbit (free-fall) precisely because it is moving
with the same angular velocity as the planetary surface.

>The 2300AD game system recognized two "Beanstalks" in the human sphere.  One
>on the earth and one at Beta Canum Venaticorum (sp?).  The whole thing was
>the asteroid was like a ball on the end of a string because of the speed it
>was orbiting the planet and its mass, greater than that of the stalk itself,
>it wanted to pull away from the planet.  In the "Invasion" module in order
>to deny the Kafer\'s  access to the beanstalk the lower attachments were
>blown before the planet fell and the beanstalk just drifted off into space.
>Musta been a hell of a sight from the planets surface.

??????! This sounds wrong to me.  The anchor mass does want to pull away
from the planet: it wants to travel in a straight line at a constant
velocity, but it can\'t because the planetary mass keeps on exerting a
gravitational pull on it.  This is pretty much the definition of "orbit" and
explains why the Moon doesn\'t need a long string attached to it to stop it
drifting away from the Earth.  Similarly, the cable anchor would stay in
orbit whether the cable was attached or not (unless it is the case that the
weight of the cable would eventually pull the anchor out of orbit...)

>        That\'s why you extend a counterweight *outward* from the central
>mass. That part is easy to fix ... but what do you do when some terrorist
>blows the downhaul loose? Or some drunk in his suborbital skimmer nails it?
>The kinetic energy in that cable when it hits will make the end of the world
>look like a day at the beach ...

In "Red Mars" the martian seperatists blow the cable at the anchor end to
stop Terran mercenaries assaulting the surface (Its a while since I read it
so I might be misremebering here).  

I\'m not sure about the idea of a counterweight: I don\'t think it would work
either (I\'m so down on everything today :-)).  A counterweight mass higher
up than the primary anchor would have a different orbital velocity.
Remember that the only reason the elevator works (if it does...) is because
its orbital velocity is such that it has the same period as the planetary
surface below, and this can only be achieved at one orbital radius.  The
counterweight would have to be both higher up than the anchor and moving at
the same velocity as the anchor and this just isn\'t possible.

In Scotland we have a third verdict in court: "Not Proven".  This is how I
feel about Space Elevators.  I really would welcome any more comments on
this subject.  If you don\'t think its appropriate for the list, mail me direct.
(jamie@tsc.scotnet.co.uk)

Thanks for the comments to date.

Jamie

