Would you say the same about the Star Wars RPG?  What about
Battlelords of the 23rd Century?  The problem with role-playing games
is that there needs to be a place for them to play in.  What you just
described is GURPS Space.

If all Traveller is suppossed to be is a set of mechanics, then why
are we even bothering including a background?  Why should Virus or The
Rebellion even be an issue?  If you don\'t like technology tied to
rules, then why is jump space the default FTL?

But the Imperium does end up being the background for the ruleset for
the game we call Traveller.  And yes, jump works the way it does,
Strephon lives, and Virus make my toaster feel queasy.

If you want to use the rules but not the setting, then do so.  The
game should be tailored to suit your needs.  You don\'t like an
explanation change it or don\'t reference it.  Try to pick up any RPG
(other than a generic one) and see if the setting can be completely
distinguished from the rules.

As for TSR and their many campaign worlds.  Greyhawk was their
official and only campaign world until 1986 when it (along with Gary
Gygax) was dropped.  At that point they created the Forgotten Realms.
It wasn\'t until the 2nd edition, and actually in the last four years
that they\'ve started this propagation of campaign worlds.

