The most common name for such structures is "beanstalk".

> Think about it: a large mass (an asteroid, say) is placed in
> planeto-stationary orbit and a cable is lowered to the planetary equator and
> anchored.  elevator cars are then run up and down the cable.  Seems simple.
> 
> However, at no point along its length is the cable (which has mass, probably
> a lot of mass) in orbit.  For example, a section of cable 200km above the
> earth\'s surface travels "around" the planet in 24h and is thus moving at a
> very much lower velocity than a satellite orbiting at the same altitude.
> The cable is therefore not "weightless", and exerts a downwards force on the
> orbiting anchor.
> 
> Is it not then the case that no matter how massive the anchor the cable
> would eventually drag it down to the planetary surface, with catastrophic
> consequences?

You missed a *vital* detail. As you lower the cable towards the ground,
you *also* let the "anchor mass" move farther out. The anchor mass,
being *farther* out exerts an *upward* force on the cable. This keeps
the "center of mass" at the geosynch point, and also keeps the cable
under tension.


