    'index' => 'ad975',
    'month' => '06',
    'body' => 'Jamie Young <jamie@tsc.scotnet.co.uk> wrote:
> Instead of "drag" I should have said "pull": the weight of the cable is
> pulling the asteroid down because although the asteroid is in free-fall, the
> cable is not.  The cable is not in orbit (free-fall) precisely because it is
> moving with the same angular velocity as the planetary surface.

No ... the asteroid isn\'t in orbit, either. 
Hang on a second, and I think I can explain it to you.

Let\'s start to build a Clarke Tower: we\'ll park a space station (or an
asteroid would work, I suppose) in geostationary orbit over the equator
somewhere, OK? 

Clearly, if the station is of any size, it\'s center of mass
is what\'s in geostationary orbit, right?  The uppermost and lowermost
extremities are not actually in orbit, you see, because they are moving with
the same speed as the station\'s center of mass.  They are, however, firmly
attached to the station, and so don\'t go flying off into space, or falling
to the ground.  If you stand at the top of the station, and let a pebble go,
it would enter a different orbit than the station was in.

Now we\'ll start building the actual tower from the station to the ground.
As we start to build, the mass of the tower on the bottom of the station
will tend to move the station\'s center of gravity down.  So, to counteract
this, we\'ll add mass to the top of the station, so that the center of mass
of the whole structure stays the same.

We keep building the tower down towards the ground, and keep adding to the
counterweight on the top of the station, until the tip of the tower reaches
the ground.

It\'s worthwhile to note that this whole thing _is_ in geostationary orbit
(even though the bottom part of the tower, on the ground, isn\'t in orbit by
itself; neither is the topmost part of the counterweight).

Once we\'ve got a firm attachment to the ground, we\'ll probably add a little
extra mass to the counterweight on top of the station.  This is so we can
increase the mass at the tip of the station (ie: the on the ground, coming
up the tower) without pulling the center of gravity of the station too low.
This will also put tension on the entire tower structure.


Arthur C. Clarke (the "inventor" of the geostationary communications
satellite) has explained the concept pretty well, and the only impediment to
actually building such a structure is the strength of the materials
required.  Structurally, Clarke Tower hangs down it\'s entire length from
orbit.  The tensile stress on the tower near the "top" (station) end is
enormous - to the point where there are no engineering materials that
you can build the tower out of (various laboratory materials indicate that
we may be able, at some point in the future, to build such a tower).

One fiction book that describes the construction of a "Clarke Tower" is
Clarke\'s _The Fountains of Paradise_; and it covers the engineering pretty
well.  He may have written non-fiction articles about it as well; I don\'t
have a bibliography handy.

> ??????! This sounds wrong to me.  The anchor mass does want to pull away
> from the planet: it wants to travel in a straight line at a constant
> velocity, but it can\'t because the planetary mass keeps on exerting a
> gravitational pull on it.  This is pretty much the definition of "orbit"

The anchor mass portion is not, repeat not, in orbit, any more than the
tower portion is in orbit.

> Similarly, the cable anchor would stay in
> orbit whether the cable was attached or not (unless it is the case that the
> weight of the cable would eventually pull the anchor out of orbit...)

No.  The entire structure, taken as a whole, is in orbit.  Remove or
separate any portion of the structure, and the remaining portions are NOT
in orbit, and will do various strange things.

> The counterweight would have to be both higher up than the anchor and
> moving at the same velocity as the anchor and this just isn\'t possible.

Yes!  It _is_ possible, as long as the counterweight is attached to the
"anchor end" of the cable.  In order to "keep up" with the anchor end of the
cable, the counterweight has to be moving at the same angular velocity.

Since it\'s higher up than the anchor, that means it\'s moving at a higher
tangential velocity.  It\'s _also_ moving at a higher tangential velocity
than an object in orbit at the same altitude [*].  This means that it
"pulls" on the anchor (if the anchor were removed, the counterweight would
go flying up to a higher orbit).  As it is, the counterweight "pulls" on the
anchor - counteracting the downward pull exerted by the cable portion.

[*] The fundamental paradox of orbital mechanics: to slow down, increase
your velocity.  To speed up, reduce your velocity.  This is because
increasing your orbital (tangential) velocity raises the altitude of your
orbit, thereby increasing the length of an orbit (more than compensating for
the increased speed), and therefore _decreases_ your angular velocity.

