    'ts-index' => '1996-06-13.ad981',
    'body' => 'At 07:14 AM 6/13/96 -0800, STu wrote:
>On 12 Jun 96 at 14:28, Daniel spewed:
>> But what were the qualities of Classic Traveller that made it such
>> a big hit in 1977?  And how can you be so certain that using those 
>> qualities will not make the game a success in 1996
>
>Actually, if you want the naked truth, its because THERE WAS NOTHING 
>ELSE OUT THERE!
>
>The RPG systems on the market in 1977 were D&D, Tunnels & Trolls, and 
>a few other Fantasy RPG\'s.  It was the first SF RPG, and therefore 
>was successful, almost by default.  

Not really.  There was Space Opera which came out probably before Traveller,
but if not, shortly there after.  It didn\'t last long.  It was very
cumbersome, the printing quality was poor (used small fonts, poorly laid
out, etc.).  Yes some people loved Space Opera.  Most picked it up, looked
at the complexity and layed it right back down.  They stepped over, saw how
clean Traveller was, the rules were simple, and it was a game that can be
played.  TSR also had Gamma World, which while it had it\'s following it did
not spring to the for front of the Sci-Fi gamer like Traveller did.

>It was an elegant system for the 
>time, but lets face it, a lot of CT looks like a greybeard at this 
>point in terms of rule system.  This is the reason for a task system,
better, more 
>comprehensive ship and craft design.  Look at the number of early 
>Traveller licensees who now make products that compete within the same niche:  
>Games Workshop (Adventure 4: Leviathan), FASA (Sky Raiders, and a ton of 
>other stuff), DGP (Soon to come out with AI, they basically designed 
>MegaTraveller).  

I think the problem with CT had to do with the expansion from the basic
game.  GDW produced a bunch of supplements which kept cash flow going, but
its like a computer program that is modified and modified, after a point,
its out of control, large and clunky.  If I want to go a friends house to
play Traveller I have to pack about 50 pounds of books.  The Hardback
Traveller Book was great because it condensed a bunch of the little books
into a nice portable, usable media + they added art work.

Mega Traveller would have been great had the typos not been there and if the
system had done a bit better job of taking all the CT books and condensing
them into several books i.e. collect all the skills together, make sure
thinks like the Book 2/High Guard inconsistancies are cleared up.

The artwork for MT was fantastic, the layout and printing was clear and
readable.  It is probably my favorite set of Traveller reference books to
work with until you get to almost every page has written notes transcribed
from the Errata.

TNE would have been successful had GDW printed it nicely and not altered the
basic flow of the game.  AD&D is still the same basic game as it was in
1977.  The expansions and inconsistices are cleaned up with each printing,
and lessons learned over the years go to make the game better.  There is no
doubt that the Players Handbook and Dungeon Masters Guide today are far
superior to the books produced in the late \'70s.  Yet the rules have only
been changed slightly, and then only to correct problems.

What sells a role playing game today?  

  a) Playable rules.
  b) Incredible Cover Art
  c) Incredible interior art
  d) Sharp printing (interior color helps).
  e) Everything you need to get started available Day 1.
     (not necessarily in the same book).

Vampire is not a complex game.  The game is not over run with rules.  More
time is given to telling the story than determining the diameter, spacing,
and depth of the bite wounds in millimeters.  No one cares that if a bite
from behind at 45 degrees yields a faster blood flow than a frontal bite at
87 degrees.

Take that specificly to Traveller:

I would rather have:

TL 12 Mk. 1 Laser        10d6 Damage
TL 12 Mk. 2 Laser        20d6 Damage
TL 13 Mk. 1 Laser        15d6 Damage etc.

than:

TL 12 150 MW Laser       10d6 Damage
TL 12 200 MW Laser       etc ...

The Laser wattage has no real game effects.  Why do you think Star Trek has
Type 1 and type 2 phasers [Rob visually holds up two different Phasers
showing that they look different]?  Because its something the masses relate to.

Keep it Simple.  Keep it playable.  Don\'t make things complex just because.  

>If you think that just reissuing the little black books in a single 
>bound volume is going to allow IG to take shelf space away from West 
>End Games (Star Wars), & FASA (Starfleet Battles), you are deluding 
>yourself.  Very few people would give a system that relied solely on something 
>as crude as Book 2, Starships for ship design a 2nd glance today, not 
>even me.

They did that with the Traveller Book and it was very popular.  But today
that wont cut it.  There has to be Art and a lot of it and there has to be a
heck of a story to pull you in.  (Oh, Star Wars is a simple game too.  No
need to be a nuclear engineer there....)  Its got to be clean and sharp.

As far as vehicles and starships go, how many games currently on the market
even let your build them?  I don\'t think Vampire lets you construct cars.
AD&D does not provide rules for building ships.  The Star Trek RPG didn\'t
include ship building, they had you buy pre-designed ships.  

Sounds like I am going back to support TNE which did not include design
sequences.  TNE did not have enough ship types, nor did it have deck plans,
nor did it provide tables for fixing shot-up components.  Also there were
way too many abbreviations that you had to did through text to find out what
it ment.  However, T4 Starships if done right will bring the coolness of the
day I first picked up Supplement 7 - Traders and Gun Boats, which is still
the coolest and most used Supplement that Marc put out.

I want a ship design facility, and the multi-level tier system looks fine so
far.  Only about 1/3 of the books sold will be sold to people who will care
to build ships (mostly refs and gear heads), but the other 2/3\'s would love
to have some solid designs and ready to go.  Ships are kind of like
Travellers "Monsters".  You have to have a monster manual with pictures and
descriptions available to oohhh and ahhh your players.  AD&D players dont
care how many vertibre are in the neck of a naga and Traveller players
certanly don\'t care how many cup holders are on board their starship.  "How
fast does it go?  How hard does it shoot?  Can I sneek around with it and
avoid those Imperial nastys?"

Enough ranting and raving...

Rob

