    'date' => 'Thu, 13 Jun 96 23:26:49  0600',
    'body' => 'On 06/13/96 at 11:53 AM,  Daniel <rkdious@metronet.com> said:

>I can\'t remember if it was Alpha Centari, but several gas giant sized
>planets have been found in orbit around other stars.  The real
>interesting fact about these new planets is that are orbiting closer
>to their star than our own systems gas giants.  

One was far sure and another *might* be, the report I saw wasn\'t
clear.  This really surprised me too.  What\'s a gas giant doing that
close?  Shouldn\'t the solar heat and wind driven off all that hydrogen
from the inner system?  One of the giants should be in the star\'s
lifezone too!

>Will this data efect the rules for star system generation?  Book
>6 states that gas giants should first be placed in outer orbits
>before being placed in inner orbits.

I doubt it.  IG has been *dead* silent on system generation, and
that\'s *my* real interest..not gloveboxes in Scout ships.  <g> The
system gen rules haven\'t changed much (any?) since book 6. My
expectation is they\'ll stay the same in T4.

>However, our own system seems to be the exception rather than
>the rule.

Too soon to say.  Some of the earlier planet sightings had giants way
out like ours are.  I\'m guessing we\'re closer to the rule than the
exception.  As the accretion disk condenses the majority of the
lighter gases are driven out of the inner system leaving smallish
metal heavy planets close in and larger hydrogen heavy planets further
out.  The break between inner and outer system seems to be where water
freezes out. 

