    'body' => 'ereddoch@amaranth.com (Eris Reddoch) writes:

> 2.  Space Loop - Link lightweight magnetic strips into a loop a couple
> of hundred miles long.  Put several strong magnetic drivers along the
> strip and start accelerating the links.  As the links accelerate along
> the ground centriphical force causes the top half of the loop to
> elevate.  At some speed the top of the loop is above the atmosphere. 
> Link in slightly more massive links as the whole thing is spinning for
> increased support.  Now construct a *lightweight* framework around the
> loop, and you can send a tram around to the top and back down on the
> framework. You could also drop an elevator cable down from the top. 
> Believe it or not, the science behind this one looks solid.  Dangerous
> as ##$@!  Probably expensive as that too..but most likely doable. The
> suggestion was to do this at sea down along the equator for safety
> sake.  This macro-lariat idea came from some folks down at Texas A&M.

I happen to *know* Keith Lofstrom, the guy who came up with this one.
He isn\'t at Texas A&M, though for all I know, he may had worked with
folks there.

The "loop" consists of a bunch of iron plates. No connection between
them. Something like this:
    +--+
    |  |
<-- |  |
    |  |
    +--+
You run them thru an evacuated tube on the ground, sort of like a mass
driver. At each end, you have *big* magnets that bend the stream
through an angle. Two sets at each end. So after going through both,
the stream is headed back to the other end, Sort of like this:

                        ->
      ----
    /                                                  \\
    ----
                        <-
It\'s around a hundred klicks between  the ends as I recall.
The reaction forces from bending the stream around require the *lower*
of each pair to be well anchored to bedrock. The upper pair "float"
supported be the thrust involved in bending the stream. They are
anchored to (kevlar?) cables to help even out any variations in thrust.

You start adding plates to the stream and extending the angled sections
of the tubing. This slowly raises the upper part of the loop. Once you
get high enough, you can can quit extending the tubing, as the air
pressure is as low as it is inside.

To use the loop, you magnetically "grapple" to the stream. As you grab
harder, it slows down and you speed up. Note that the upper section of
the loop is the slowest and it is still somewhat above orbital
velocity.  

Anyway, you just let the "drag" from the stream of plates against your
magnetic field drag you on up, and on the upper section, either boost
you to orbital velocity, or brake you. 

The worst thing that can happen is failure of one of the 4 "corner"
magnets. If it\'s the "up" magnet on the ground, you just let the steram
of plates fly through a gap in the magnet and break through a
replaceable pressure seal. They wind up in the ocean. You generate a
*lot* of steam, and rusty ocean water. :-) And you are out the energy
you invested in speeding up the plates, and the cost of the plates. The
energy is the most expensive part. The upper stations will have
parachutes. So re-erecting is an annoyance.

If the "down" ground station fails, due to the angle, you can still
dump into the ocean, but you want deeper water there.

If the ascending station on the upper portion fails, you lose a bunch
of plates, as they\'ll be above escape velocity. If the descending
station fails, you\'ll have a shitload of plates in orbit, and a fair
chance of recovering them. 

The loop concept would be well suited to atmosphere 0,1 and 2 worlds.
Beanstalks are suited to smaller worlds, regardless of atmosphere.
Tether systems (skyhooks) are workable on just about anything, but how
workable depends on details of the planetary system. Space fountains
are best for low g worlds, I\'d think. Low atmosphere would help.





