    'body' => 'Jamie Young (jamie@tsc.scotnet.co.uk) said:

:>I think that the most likely candidate for drag is going to be the effect
:>of the planet\'s atmosphere on the cable, but I don\'t have any figures for
:>that, I\'m afraid.

:I shouldn\'t have used the term "drag" - I meant it in the loose rather than
:technical sense.  The cable isn\'t being pulled through the planet\'s
:atmosphere, although I imagine that strong winds near the ground and
:high-altitude jetstreams might have an effect on the structure.  Instead of
:"drag" I should have said "pull": the weight of the cable is pulling the
:asteroid down because although the asteroid is in free-fall, the cable is
:not.  The cable is not in orbit (free-fall) precisely because it is moving
:with the same angular velocity as the planetary surface.

   Methinks you misunderstand the concept of Beanstalks.

   Now, I hope you understand the basics of orbital mechanics, but just in
   case here\'s arefresher.

   Objects stay in orbit by going just fast enough (but no faster) to be
   continually racing against gravity. Gravity pulls on the object, and
   the object travels *just* far enough that the amount that it falls
   matches the curvature of the planet. Orbital mechanics is influenced
   by a number of factors; gravity, the size/density of the planet being
   orbited, and the amount of drag encountered (primarily a concern at
   lower altitudes, say less than 150km) Gravity varies (using the inverse
   square law) depending on the distance from the planetary surface. This
   means that objects closer to the planet have to orbit faster.
   Clear so far?

   Knowing this much, a couple of things become obvious:

   1) Objects in orbit can match the rotational period of the planet in
      *only* one orbital band. (In Earth orbit, this is approximately
      20-25k miles)

   2) Objects matching the rotational period of the planet, but *closer*
      will fall from orbit. Objects matching the rotational period of the
      planet, but *farther* will leave orbit and fly away.

   Now picture this:

   A space station is put into orbit where it can match the rotational
   period of the planet. This space station has two reels of _very_ strong
   cable inside. Two BIG counterweights are attached to these LARGE reels of
   cable. Start reeling these cables, one leads DOWN to the planets surface,
   the other leads OUTWARDS into interplanetary space.

   Two things begin happening almost immediately:

   1) The LOWER counterweight is going _slower_ than it needs to be to
      stay in orbit, it will tug downwards on the space station. The
      farther down it goes, the harder it pulls.

   2) The HIGHER counterweight is going _faster_ than it\'s needs to be to
      stay in orbit, it will tug upwards into space. The farther out it
      goes, the harder it pulls.

   Keep going until you reach the surface.

   The biggest problem we face to construct a Beanstalk is NOT the orbital
   mechanics, but the sheer strength of the materials needed to withstand
   the stresses of such a construct. The two cables will have to be about
   50K miles total, and will not only have to carry the load it\'s lifting
   to orbit, but it will have to be strong enough to support itself, and
   that\'s no mean feat!

   You will also notice that *any* kind of failure in the structure is
   disastrous. The parts of the structure leading down to the surface are
   travelling *less* than orbital velocity. If a terrorist group planted a
   bomb on an elevator, and blew it up halfway up the stalk, the lower half
   of the cable would drop and hit like a bomb. Worse, it would be long
   enough to wrap itself around the Earth hitting a VERY large area and
   virtually certain to blast a large chunk of the ocean into the atmosphere
   causing some serious and longlasting problems with the ecosphere. (eg,
   nuclear winter or greenhouse effect - take your pick)


