    'body' => 'On Sun, 16 Jun 1996, Stuart L. Dollar wrote:

> Yeah, but you gotta admit that Gygax & GDW did give TSR some 
> ammunition...

In a way, yes.  But, heck, was Gygax supposed to never write another FRPG 
again?  Never write an RPG of any type again?  

Let\'s assume Gygax left TSR, THEN decided to come up with a new FRPG 
because he felt that not being saddled with the traditions of D&D, and 
having quite a bit more experience at writing RPG\'s than he had when he 
originally started, would allow him to make a really great product.  He 
contacts GDW, and they agree to publish it, since he is a "name" and they 
like the idea of filling out their line with a FRPG.  

If something like that was the case, what should they have done in order 
to avoid giving TSR ammunition?  Should Gygax be barred from making 
FRPG\'s?  If so, TSR should have paid him to agree to that (it\'s been done 
- - Nolan Bushnell, the man who founded Atari, signed a five-year non-competition 
agreement with Warner Communications when they forced him out).  

Unless TSR had evidence that Gygax had worked on the game while he was in 
their employ - using TSR\'s facilities, equipment, supplies, and/or time - 
then they had no basis for their claim.

This is all speculation, of course.  It\'d be great to know what really 
happened.


- -Joe
