>whole  role-playing industry caters to a fringe group.

That is absolutely true. If you use the term, "Role-Playing Game," people
have no idea what you\'re talking about. If you say, "You know, like
Dungeons & Dragons," immediately the realization of what you\'re talking
about crosses their face, and they wonder why you, as a grown man (in
my case), are playing games meant for pimply-faced adolescents. The
general public doesn\'t realize that this is the hobby of many people, and
that a whole industry supports it.

>Remember JC Penney selling TSR products, including D&D and
>Dungeon?  They  also sold some Grenadier models.  This was back in
>82-83.  

Yup. I got my first (and my last :) copy of Dungeons and Dragons from
Jamesway (a now-bankrupt department store, like Kmart) when I was a
kid.

>Man, if IG  and FFE could get the Traveller name out there like Marc has 
>been talking about, there\'s no limit to the sales potential.  Which  brings
>up a point I worry about: popularity generally means the product  has
>been homoginized beyond the point where I can continue to enjoy it.  
>Will the traditional Traveller be something the masses want, once they 
>are made aware of it via TV, movies, and books?  Or will it be
>necessary  to dilute the product in order to gain that mass audience?

I don\'t think so. I was always a fan of Star Trek, even before the movies.
Now that it has exploded in popularity, I\'m extremely happy, because that
means that Paramount feels it is worth it to pump more money into the
project. So when I once had only 76 original-series episodes to watch,
now I\'ve got the original series, 7 movies, and three TV series to watch,
and another movie is coming out in November. I\'ve got a copy of the Star
Trek RPG (original version--which I believe also came out of the JC Penny
catalog in about \'82), and I get the Star Trek Communicator magazine.
That\'s enough for me, but there\'s a ton more Star Trek stuff out there I
could get involved in (I\'ve never been to a convention) if I felt it was
worth the time. Because of its popularity, I can now immerse myself in
Star Trek. And it hasn\'t been diluted one bit. There\'s still the same
techno-speak there always was. If anything, it\'s been expanded.

Wouldn\'t you enjoy it if the same thing happened to Traveller? If
somebody didn\'t know what a RPG was, and you said to them, "You
know, like Traveller." Or to have Traveller novels, TV series, movies, etc. I
think that would be fantastic! And the point is, it can happen. If Paramount
could do it with Star Trek, which is sort of pseudo-military based, don\'t
you think it could be done with Traveller, which can focus more on the
non-military-type adventures? I think it can, and I think it will.

