    'subj' => 'Midnight at the Well of Souls (wince, shudder)',
    'from' => 'FKiesche3@aol.com',
    'body' => 'Greetings:

Well, after glancing at 600 or so pages of digests, I see my (mostly)
throwaway line about notes for a Midnight at the Well of Souls generated some
interest.

Some background is in order, then...

Set the wayback machine for 1977. Star Wars is out. Traveller is out. Some
early Jack Chalker--Jungle of Stars, Midnight, Web of the Chozen is out. Fred
Kiesche, Ron Fischer and a few others are at Rutgers University. The pot is
stirred.

In those early days, there wasn\'t much structure to the Traveller universe. I
remember my roommate Ron going to Origins and bringing back exciting news
about Traveller (AHL! Fifth Frontier Wars!). But we mostly ran our own stuff,
based on a weird mixture of Larry Niven, Jack Chalker and others.

One adventure we ran was--well, we never really had a name, but called it
(jokingly) "The Web of the Bloodretch". It was a weird mixture of Jack
Chalker\'s Web of the Chozen and Midnight at the Well of Souls, with character
transformations into an alien spieces, a wrecked alien culture, and a quest
to transform the characters back into humans. It was fun, but it was bad.

Fast forward a little. Add in Steve Davidson, somebody who actually knows
Jack Chalker. We\'re all talking about doing something, publishing
something...so of course we think of doing a RPG based on Midnight.

The race is on. We call GDW. We do a conference call with Loren Wiseman and
Marc Miller. We get tentative permission to use Traveller (sans Imperium
background) for Midnight the RPG. We contact Eleanor Wood Agency about Jack
Chalker. We start negotiations.

Enter Tim A. Green of TAG Industries, mostly known (at that point) for sewing
bags to hold dice.

TAG Industries and Davidson/Kiesche start a bidding war for the rights to
Midnight. TAG is backed by Tim\'s father, who has (we hear) $$$. We only have
$, generated by our salaries and savings. $$$ beats out $, so we lose out.
The project collapses on our end.

I toss my notes in a fit of anger.

About a year later, TAG comes out with Midnight. Plans are announced--Basic
RPG, lots of modules, a board game based on the Wars of the Well World
(sequels numbers 2, 3, 4), miniatures, etc.

The game bombs. The game does not sell. The game bites big time. TAG vanishes
from the map.

Who knows what would have happened if we had the rights and were able to slap
"Based on the Traveller system" on the front?

Web of the Bloodretch still exists in a few pages of notes, somewhere. As
with my first "dungeon" for Empire of the Petal Throne, it\'s rather sketchy
and pretty awful. But you can\'t toss some things...

Fred Kiesche
(FKiesche3@aol.com)
