    'index' => 'ae204',
    'body' => 'At 11:18 AM 6/19/96 -0400, you wrote:

>recently there has been a lot of talk on xboat about FTL drives.  I was
>wondering if someone could take the time to expain what a stutterwarp
>drive is.  Sorry for my ignorance, but I\'ve never played 2300 (I think
>thats where stutterwarp came from), but it sounds interesting. 

The stutterwarp used a macro scale of the electron tunneling effect.  The
whole thing was some fellow, Dean, discovered that given the correct
circumstances electrons could disappear from one point and reappear
instantaniously several cm away.

Utilizing this knowledge the stutterwarp "tunnels" the ship it is  contained
in several hundred meters ahead by cycling the drive thousands of times a
second, getting the revs up, the ship could be made to travel at multiple
velocities of C when in deep space.  Stutterwarp is also limited by gravity
wells so the further a ship gets into a gravity well the less efficinetly
the drive works untill it completely konks out at 0.1 G.  After that you
need conventional thrusters.

What this means is that the ship has no actual forward momentum so
technically it\'s not breaking and laws of Einstineian physics.  Because it
lacks forward momentum it can turn on a dime and accellerate and decellerate
far faster than a regular starship which has to counteract all that momentum.

Because the ship is moving faster than C the first thing your sensors would
show is as it went past you.  Remember it\'s leaping in front of it\'s old
sensor image.  What this means is if two stutterwarp ships passed each other
in deep space a person staring out the window of one ship would see the
other ship suddenly materialize directly in front of their window then
receed off in both directions.  One as the ship actually leaves and the
other as the ships approaching images arrive to be seen.  Looking out the
back of a stutterwarp ship that turned off it\'s drive would produce and
equally interesting effect as all the images behind you caught up in reverse
order, so you\'d see the ship receed off into the distance as the images
caught up to you.  Pretty cool eh?

I hope this gives you a better handle on stutterwarp drives.  I could quote
it all from FF&S if you\'d like.  It\'s a little more concise and gearheaded
in there.

DS

