    'date' => 'Wed, 19 Jun 96 21:07:10 PST',
    'body' => 'ereddoch@amaranth.com (Eris Reddoch) writes:

> If you want to introduce alternate FTL tech you can, but Jump is the
> \'canon\' approach.  
> 
> I\'ve used stutterwarp, hyperdrive, and ST-like warp drive in the past,
> but I\'ve always limited FTL to just one way per game.  I could see
> independent development of 2 or 3 methods, but I don\'t know if that
> situation would continue long.  Wouldn\'t the best way soon become the
> way everyone used?

"Best" for *what*? Each type is going to have good points and bad
points. So what may be good for *some* things might be lousy for
others. 

As an example, take the Habegger gates F. M. Busby has been using in
recent works. You stuff things in one end, and it comes out the other
end. No time passes for anything in transit, but two years pass for the
outside world. And they don\'t have a range limit.

So they\'d be great for bulk cargo, and for colonization. But they\'d be
lousy for general travel, and for urgent cargo. They\'d be a dead loss
for most military uses. 

They\'d make little difference in the Imperium (and in fact, they\'d
explain the lack of bulk cargo carriers). And the X-boat routes would
still be very important (who wants two year-old news, if you can get it
only a few months old?).

This is an extreme case, but most FTL drives in fiction have limits of
some sort, if only because it makes for better story possibilities.


Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
