    'body' => 'derek stanley <dstanley@direct.ca> writes:

> At 11:33 AM 6/18/96 -0400, you wrote:
> >>Well, I suppose that shows that in ALL traveller there are different
> >>styles of stardrives, but the TNE book also goes on to say that only ONE
> >>should be allowed in each universe (kind of dumb if you ask me).
> >
> >I think it\'d be a really cool campaign to have the characters encounter an
> >alien race who uses warp technology. It\'d be really interesting if the
> >players had to flee a space combat situation: their ship would disappear
> >into jump space, and the aliens would be like, "Hey, man, what
> >happened?"
> 
> Actually thats FF&S that says that not TNE.  And in a round about way it
> makes sence.  There should only be one method of travelling between the
> stars, only one way of breaking the laws of physics.  Granted it would be
> cool to watch the aliens faces when that happened.

Actually, there\'s no reason to suppose that there is only *one* way to
do something. Consider flight. There\'s lighter than air, aerodynamic
lift, and overwhelming thrust. For interplanetary travel, there are
reaction drives, solar sails, etc.

Which you use depends in part on what you want to accomplish. For any
particular task, one method is usually much better than the others. But
that doesn\'t mean that you can\'t do it other ways.

There may be several ways of achieving FTL. Certainly the current
theories sugest at least two *different* methods (wormholes and the
Alucubierre drive).

And as a previous post suggested, if you are careful to adjust the
performance and limitations of various technologies, you can have
multiple drive types with no real problems.

Heck, it could even turn out that after the "warp drive" and "jump
drive" folks get to know each other, they\'ll both think that the other
is *nuts* for using the drive they do. 

"If that warp drive breaks down, you\'re stuck out in deep space and
have to hope someone can find you."

"So? At least they\'ll know *where* to look for us. If that Jump drive
of yours mis-jumps, you could wind up *anywhere*!"

(and round and rond they go... :-)

