    'month' => '06',
    'index' => 'ae260',
    'body' => 'Eris Reddoch wrote:

>Oh BTW, how does a Stutterwarp match orbital velocity with a planet? 
>Or even worse, how would it match velocity with deep space base?  It\'s
>got to have some *real* thrust coming from somewhere!

The rules governing stutterwarps in 2300AD required that ships spend around
40 hours discharging in a gravity well every 7.7 light years travelled. 
This well had to be higher than .1g, at which point the warp efficiency
plummeted to "poor chemical thruster" levels.  In my campaigns using this
system, much of the time spent discharging was used alternatively
free-falling deeply into the well and stuttering back to the .1g limit
again.  The net effect of this is to accumulate a new (real space) vector
of the right amount for your next destination.  For a high example, forty
hours at 1g is certainly enough (144km/s) for most nearby stellar
velocities and well over anything required within systems. 

a.goddard@strath.ac.uk
