    'body' => 'On 21 Jun 96 at 15:13, Jamie Young spewed:

> How was the Imperium organised during its heyday? Was it an elective

Actually, for the most part, the Imperium was dynastic.  There was 1 
period when this ceased to be true.  The Civil War of 604-622 
occurred when Olav Hault-Plankwell, Grand Admiral of the Marches, 
assassinated Empress Jacqueline.  Olav was the 2nd Emperor to succeed 
by right of assassination.  The first, which had removed Cleon the 
Mad, had been sanctioned by the moot.  The murder of Jacqueline 
kicked off a 2 decade period where basically any admiral who had 
control of a few fleets, a lot of ambition, and more nerve, could 
move his fleet into the Core sector, kill off the last admiral to 
kill the Emperor, and become Emperor himself.  These Emperors were 
the so called Barracks Emperors.  This might have gone on in indefinitely, 
except for Arbellatra, who knocked off the last of the Barracks 
Emperors.  Arbellatra, unlike her predecessors, knew that she would not be 
immediately supported as Emperor.  She proclaimed herself Regent, 
promising to rule only until a legitimate heir to the throne could be 
found.  Of course, anybody with any sort of legitimate claim to the 
throne was basically freeze dried meat in space, or 2 meters 
underground at the time, so the net result was that Arbellatra 
became Emperor a few years later.

This restored the principle of dynastic succession, which continued 
until the assassination of Strephon in 1116 by Dulinor.  At this 
point, the Imperium ceased to exist as a single, unified entity.

Theoretically, the Moot is supposed to approve Imperial candidates, 
but with about 3 exceptions, it acted as a rubber stamp body. 

1)  When Cleon the Mad became emperor, the moot actively plotted his 
assassination, and his murderer was proclaimed Emperor by right of 
Assassination.

2) The vast majority of the Barracks Emperors were never approved by 
the Moot.

3)  The Moot never got an opportunity to approve or deny Lucan\'s 
claim to the throne after the deaths of Strephon, his heir, and 
Varian (Lucan\'s older brother) during the Rebellion.  Lucan fearing 
what the Moot might have to say, dissolved it for a year, and then 
began to stuff the Moot to his favor by disenfranchising numerous 
nobles who opposed him, and granting new titles and fiefs to a number 
of his lackeys.

> claimants. Was the Imperium prone to such internal strife (prior to the
> Rebellion)?

See comments on Civil War above...

> What did the Emperor\'s job involve?  I assume he/she must have had real
> power otherwise the position would\'nt be worth killing for.  On a similar
> vein, what was the source of the Emperor\'s wealth - was he obliged to live
> off the revenues of his own estates or could he raid the Imperial treasury
> at will?

The Imperial family had vast holdings in most of the megacorporation, 
as well as fiefs on numerous worlds.  Don\'t know about your comments 
on raiding the Imperial treasury, but if their holdings in the 
megacorps amounted to what they should, I doubt any of the Emperors 
ever wanted for money.  Somebody else could probably 
answer this question better than I could.

Stu
 
