Isn\'t this what both the Aslan and the Vargr serve to do in Traveller? ;)
 
> In Next Generation, they were portrayed with kind of a Code of 
> Bushido air to them (honor was more important than life, etc).

Yes, this is fairly Aslan.

> Now in DS9, they\'re portrayed almost as a race at war with itself, in 
> a near constant state of turmoil...hence my Vargr comparisons...

I think the idea is that there\'s a big battle for control of the Klingon
race... this is actually not unlike the Aslan, where there are
various competing clans, who fight not only outsiders (Imperium/.
Solomani) but each other. There are distinct, clear clan lines
that can be drawn for the Aslan however, unlike the Vargr, who,from
a human perspective, seem to fight with anyone.

I think the Aslan are motivated somewhat by the Kzin (Kzinti?)
of Larry Niven\'s "Known Space" universe.

If I was to risk being a cynic, I\'d also note that both the Aslan
and the Vargr suffer badly from the "humans in rubber suits"
syndrome. The K\'kree are a bit better, then the Droyne and the
Hivers are probably the most alien aliens. Though none of
the Traveller aliens could be described as "bad head jobs"
(well, not much).

Ethan
