Mark Seemann <mark@dk-online.dk> writes:

> The guy wants to buy a forensic kit, and that\'s fine with me. But I
> would like to detail that kit a little to tell him what it consists of,
> and what he can use it for. What would a high tech forensic kit be like?
> What does it contain?
>
> I\'d guess at some tools to sample fingerprints and other traces of the
> perpetrator, a camera, small sample holding bags, tweezers, magnifying
> glass and so on. Most of these things are pretty low tech, though.
>
> Does anyone has any ideas what a TL13 and/or a TL15 (to name two
> examples) forensic kit might contain?

You\'ll have to decide if these fit the tech level, but off the top of
my head:

o     mass-spectrographic analyzer
o     various "scanners" for examining objects and surfaces at high
     resolution and various wavelengths
o     possibly nanotech "ants" that search for traces of hair, skin,
     fiber, oils, etc under the control of the cpu in the kit


Basicly, you set the thing down, describe the area to search (room,
structure, area of ground) and it sends out the "ants", to look for
anything that might bear checking out. They record the location of
anything small enough to carry and bring it back for analysis. Larger
objects are either called to the attention of the investigator or
carried by multiple "ants".

So the tiniest drop of blood or strand of hair will be found, and a DNA
analysis run, giving you a rough picture of the person. Sure, you\'ll
get *lots* of data, but so what? As with fingerprints now, you\'ll get
samples from the people known to have been in the area, and try to
track down the unknowns.

Of course, *professional* criminals will have similar kits to "tidy up"
the scene. :-)

Luckily, professionals are rare.
Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
