> - to provide a rationale for that.


Hell, many aliens (and *most* players) are not just "humans in funny
suits". They are "contemporary Western Culture humans in funny suits".

I\'ve seen enough "role-players" who couldn\'t even take into account the
way that *humans* from a different culture react differently, to say
nothing of considering *alien* motivations. As an example, an idiot
who got in an argument with a "samurai" type character over some action
the group was taking. The idiot was about to state the the "samurai\'s"
word wasn\'t good enough when he *literally* got tackled by the less
idiotic types. This guy would probably offer a K\'kree a hamburger...

Players who *can* handle different cultures manage to handle aliens
moderately well. But they are rare. <sigh>

Gordon Dickson has written some books that have aliens who are truly
alien. That is, they are logical, reasonable beings. But the very basis
of their thought/culture is quite different. In one case, the main
difference between us and them was that our culture is "based" on
"rightness". That is, a thing is good or bad depending on how "right"
it is. For the aliens, it was "respectable/not respectable" or at least
that\'s the closest humans could come to the concept. Not that this is
*not* "honor" it\'s something more than a little different. And unless
you could keep it in mind *all* the time, the aliens would keep doing
the unexpected.

Then of course, we have C.J. Cherryh. I\'d *love* to see what\'d happen
if you placed her "Compact" just the other side of the K\'kree and
Hivers. K\'kree trying to deal with Kif would be fun. And Sshto and
mahendosat trying to deal with Hivers (and vice versa) would be almost
as good.


Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
