    'body' => 'I\'m no atmospheric scientist, but I\'ll take a stab at Jamie\'s questions,
since no one else has leaped forward....

Quoth Jamie Young:
> What would the climate of a water-world, say n-86Annn-n, in the habitable
> zone be like?

Much more temperate than Earth\'s.  With no mountain ranges or thermally-
active coastline barriers, the atmosphere would form just two convective
Hadley cells rather than the multitude that Earth has.  Water is also a
wonderful leveller of temperature variations: in past geologic eras on
Earth, the continental arragements that have allowed the greatest oceanic
circulation both north-south and east-west have tended to foster the most
consistent and idyllic climates.

> Would atmospheric currents form latitudinal bands, as on
> Jupiter?

No: Jupiter gets those bands because of its horrific rotation rate. I\'m
unsure whether they\'ve yet decided (perhaps Galileo will help?) whether
the ?solid? body of Jupiter rotates faster than does its atmosphere.

> Would the oceanographic/atmospheric interaction be unstable
> leading to global ice-ages?

I\'m not sure what you mean by this.  Could you elaborate?

> How would the climate differ between two
> waterworlds, one with a shallow global ocean and one with a deep global
> ocean?

The shallow one\'s climate is likely to vary more, as subsurface mountain
ranges, volcanoes, etc. will have a greater effect on global circulation
patterns.  So you\'d possibly get significant regional variations (like
ice caps).

> I understand that photdisassociation of atmospheric water would give
> rise to free atmospheric oxygen - it is possible to predict what percentage
> of the resulting atmosphere would be oxygen?

Free oxygen is pretty durn reactive stuff.  I suspect much of it would
come out of the atmosphere to be dissolved in the world-ocean, which it
would in turn depart to oxidize seafloor mineral outcroppings.  You
wouldn\'t get a significant fraction of atmospheric oxygen unless and until
life arose.  As for the end ratio.... the main brake on our current level
of atmospheric oxygen is the danger of fire at high levels, but that
wouldn\'t be as much of a danger on a waterworld, so perhaps it would hit
the upper 20%\'s?  (That\'s a hand-waving guess).

