    'body' => 'Jamie Young <jamie@tsc.scotnet.co.uk> writes:
> What would be the climate of a water-world... <snip>  Would the
> oceanographic/atmospheric interaction be unstable leading to
> global ice-ages?

I\'m no eco-scientist, but the first thing I thought of when I saw
this question was the carbon-cycle which tends to regulate temperature
on Earth. The general idea, and somebody with more schooling can feel
free to correct me if I get it wrong, is that carbon-dioxide plays a
huge role in determining how much heat your atmosphere retains. The more
CO2 is the air, the more heat is retained. The cycle works as follows:

1. CO2 is on the upswing, the atmosphere is heating up, which causes the
   weather system to accelerate, meaning more rain, which washes the
   CO2 back into the soil where it gets stuck for millions of years in
   the form of various carbonates, meaning that your planet cools off
   again.

2. CO2 is on the downswing, so the atmosphere cools down and the
   whether patterns slow down. Fortunately, since Earth is geologically
   active, some volcano erupts somewhere and spews out lots of CO2,
   and so the planet gets to heat up again.

Now, it gets a lot more complex than this, but for a thumbnail sketch,
this is my understanding of how Earth stays at roughly the same temperature
year after year. #2 is a constant pressure, and #1 is the opposite pressure
which due to the weather system tends to perfectly offset #2. The problem
with a water world, of course, is that #2, the constant pressure of
volcanos spewing millions of tons of CO2, is pretty much non-existant
as far as I can tell. I suppose they could be spewing CO2 from underwater,
and that it could rise to the surface in the form of bubbles, but I
wonder what percentage would be captured by the water on the way up, or
trapped under ice assuming the world went into an ice age? Another question
to consider: Without a freestanding soil, would the #1 effect, the washing
down of CO2 and trapping it various carbonates, be able to occur? If so,
as what rate as compared with a terranorm world?

Any chemists/environmentalists want to take a stab at this?

jimv@empirenet.com

