    'body' => 'Quoth Jim Vassilakos:
> The problem with a water world, of course, is that #2, the constant pressure
> of volcanos spewing millions of tons of CO2, is pretty much non-existant
> as far as I can tell. I suppose they could be spewing CO2 from underwater,
> and that it could rise to the surface in the form of bubbles, but I wonder
> what percentage would be captured by the water on the way up, or trapped
> under ice assuming the world went into an ice age?

Earth\'s oceans are already our largest CO2 reservoir, holding far more 
than the atmosphere.  In fact, one of the big questions in greenhouse
warming is just how much more CO2 might dissolve in the oceans at 
equilibrium rather than stay in the atmosphere.  So, yes, underwater
volanoes would contribute to atmospheric CO2: their effect would just
be muted/slowed by the need for gas diffusion through the oceans.

> Without a freestanding soil, would the #1 effect, the washing
> down of CO2 and trapping it various carbonates, be able to occur? If so,
> as what rate as compared with a terranorm world?

Again, dissolved CO2 might have a similar effect on seafloor deposits 
(especially new and unoxidized minerals flung from the aforesaid volcanoes).
But the need for diffusion through the ocean again slows the process down:
the waterworld might be vulnerable to wide temperature swings before its
slower feedback process brings the climate back under control.

