    'month' => '07',
    'topic' => ' Ship Names',
    'body' => 'I think a lot of ships names are somewhat under blown.  Who want\'s to be 
a crewmember on board the INV Mortimer Strain?

"Mortimer Strain?"

"Ya he\'s some guy who earned a Starburst of Extreme Heroism 800 years 
ago."

"Really, what\'d he do?"

"Nobody\'s really sure anymore."

While its a nice honor to have a ship named after you most people do not 
have names that sound "heroic" enough or have a really good mythos 
involved with their creation.

Here\'s a couple of names I\'ve used in my campaign

Artemis
Dyonitia
Athena
Aries
Hecate
etc.

Any God\'s name, with a few possible exceptions makes a good ships name.  
If the people know what the god stood for they can generally work out the 
ships purpose.

Ishtar:  Is a good name, unfortunately some fool in Hollywood made a 
totally crappy movie with the same title, forever ruining the name for 
the rest of us.

Large Imperial Vessels I generally give formidable sounding names.  
Something that strikes fear in the heart of god generally works well.

Vengence
Formidable
Victorious
Relentless
Intrepid
Triumphant
etc.

Thou these make more Solomani sounding names they\'ve got that edge that 
makes players think that something is bound to go wrong.  Merchant ships 
are probably the easiest ships to name.  Just about any name will do.

Drop Dead Red
Void Runner
Astral Waters
Silent Explorer
Ted\'s Ship
etc.

I don\'t know maybe I put to much thought into it but runnig into the same 
ship several times tends to build a sence of comaradarie.

"You slide into port there\'s (roll roll roll) two subsidized merchants 
and a far trader in port"

"You slide into port there are three ships in port, a pair os subsidized 
merchants you\'ve never seen before and the "Mistress of the Dark."

You don\'t even have to tell the players what the "Mistress" is if they\'ve 
encountered it twice before they\'ll remember the ship and it\'s crew.

"Say that\'s Captian Rumm\'s ship isn\'t it?  200ton TL-15 far trader."

"Yep, the original puking dog."

I always keep around a list of the starships my players have encountered 
and when I\'m playing I always keep track of the starships I\'ve 
encountered, type, captian and notible features.

It adds a feeling of continuity to the game that\'s often hard to find.

Derek Stanley

