    'body' => 'Jim Vassilakos <jimv@e2.empirenet.com> writes:

> with a water world, of course, is that #2, the constant pressure of
> volcanos spewing millions of tons of CO2, is pretty much non-existant
> as far as I can tell. I suppose they could be spewing CO2 from underwater,
> and that it could rise to the surface in the form of bubbles, but I
> wonder what percentage would be captured by the water on the way up, or
> trapped under ice assuming the world went into an ice age? Another question
> to consider: Without a freestanding soil, would the #1 effect, the washing
> down of CO2 and trapping it various carbonates, be able to occur? If so,
> as what rate as compared with a terranorm world?

You do get CO2 from underwater volcanos. It pretty much goes into
solution. *But*, the the concentration of CO2 in the water has to match
that of the atmosphere. This is actually shifted a bit by solubility,
but the basic idea hold. The CO2 content of surface water depends on
the amount in the air, and the temperature of the water. The CO2
content at depth depends on the temperature, and the content of any
adjacent water, modified by how fast CO2 diffuses. 

Given the lack of exposed rock, the carbonate formation would only
happen to exposed rock on the bottom. CO2 makes water acidic, so it
will react with basic rocks, resulting in carbonates. Also, calcium
carbonate is a favored structural material of some life forms, so they
will create it from the calcium dissolved in the water. 

The carbon cycle change more slowly, asnd thus be more capable of
taking large swings if some sudden change happens, but it should still
work out.

Remember that the main reason for the runaway greenhouse on Venus is
the *lack* of water. 

As I recall from discussions of Ice Ages, a water world is less likely
to do this. The reason we have so many is because of all the land in
the northern hemisphere. When the continents are more spread out, we
don\'t get ice ages.

There are two reasons for this. First, when water gets to 4C, it
reaches maximum density and sinks. That causes a circulation pattern
that moves surface waters north (and coriolis forces turn this eats or
west, depending on hemisphere), and deep waters move south. If you do
manage to freeze the surface water, it has to be in a land-locked area
like a lake or the Arctic Ocean. On a water world, you\'d have to get
most of the oceans *volume* to 4C before it could *start* to freeze.

And once the surface freezes, it insulates the deeper whater against
further heat loss. So as long as the equilibrium temp of the planet (as
determined by solar radiation) is above freezing, you\'ll have at least
some open whatever, barring so *really* weird occurences.


