    'from' => 'Eris Reddoch',
    'body' => 'On 07/10/96 at 07:04 AM,  Derek Stanley <dstanley@direct.ca> said:

> This is because originally the keyboard was set up to slow down the 
>of the typist.  The first keyboard developed, back in the 1800\'s, was
>an  extremely fast keyboard the problem was if you typed at maximum
>speed the  striker type arms all got jammed up at the type place, who
>can remember  this?  

Me!  Me!  I learned to type on a manual typewriter, complete with
striker arms. 

Derek\'s right about the keyboard layout.  The typewriter was invented
in 1871, and every manufacturer had his own layout, each better and
faster than everybody else.  The problem was the men (women weren\'t
allowed to type...their fingers were considered too delicate <g>) kept
jamming the keys.  In 1878, I think it was, a committee decided on a
standard keyboard layout..that we call QWERTY..that every manufacturer
*could* use.  The QWERTY layout was designed to slow typists down and
particularly move certain key combos to locations requiring a reach.

Today with electronic typewriters/keyboards we don\'t need the QWERTY
layout, but it\'s unlikely to go away.  Typing teachers know QWERTY, so
they teach QWERTY, and their students become the typing teachers who
teach what they learned...QWERTY. <G>

Dr Dvorak developed a much better layout in the early 1930\'s.  His
layout was tested against QWERTY:  2 typists typed the same documents
during an 8 hour day with movie cameras recording their finger
movements, the distance their fingers moved during the the 8 hours of
typing were measured.  The QWERTY typist\'s fingers moved more than 3
miles, while the Dvorak\'s typist\'s fingers moved around 1/2 mile.

Eris, 
    the font of useless trivia <G>
