    'month' => '07',
    'topic' => ' Alternate Weapon Paradigms',
    'body' => 'In somewhere mysterious you write:

> I am curious if anyone has developed weapons from an alternate
> culture or race that follow a different paradigm than 20th century
> Earth.  Obviously, there are only so many ways to design a weapon
> that propels a high-velocity object over a distance to it\'s target,
> but what if a culture never developed chemical propellants?  What
> would their weapon paradigm be?

> I thought perhaps a culture might have a curved weapon launcher of
> some sort (think jai alai).  Perhaps if they did eventually create
> explosives of some sort they might still propel the explosive down a
> curved barrel.

Curved barrels are decidely non-optimal for any kind of projectile
propelled by a push. They\'d be hard to aim, and the wear on the outside
of the curve would be extreme. They\'d also have a tendency to blow up.

Missile weapons progress through several somewhat parallel sequences,
and gun powder comes in fairly late.

centifugal force:

           Thrown rockthrown spear
        |     |
       sling -+- jai alai stick  atlatl
              | 
        staff sling
     |
         trebuchet

torsion/tension:
     
       bow
        |
crossbow/ballista

pressure:

       gunpowder  airsteam
           |   |  |
  cannon/handcannonblowgun    steam cannon
         |   |
  guns/artilleryair rifle

"rocket":

"firearrows"
    |
 rocket
    |
congreve rocket
    |
missile/bazooka/gyrojet  

electromagnetic:

mass driver/rail gun

I can\'t think of any missile weapons that don\'t fit one of these
categories (except maybe the boomerang).

I can\'t really see torsion/tension weapons going much farther than they
did. Ditto for pressure and rocket. You run into materials limits
pretty fast. 

On the other hand, there *are* some possibilities with centrifugal
force. Take the old "turbine" that Heron invented in ancient Greece. It
never got used for anything. But imagine someone noticing the way that
anything "loose" near the ends of the nozzles flys off pretty hard.

With a some work, you could come up with a gizmo that dropped stones
from a hopper into "boxes" one the side of the "turbine". Remember, it
spun about a *horizontal* axis. Sort of like a miniature waterwheel
attached to the same shaft.

It wouldn\'t be very effective, but it\'d be enough to make people keep
tinkering with it. Eventually, you\'d wind up with a *nasty* little
weapon. A steam turbine coupled to a set of appropriately curved
compartments that get fed balls at one point and eject them down a
barrel after say half a revolution or so. Look up the rpm of even an
19th century steam turbine, and figure out what sort of velocity we are
talking about with only a meter radius.

It might even be possible to design one around a compact gas turbine,
in which case you\'d have a rifle like weapon with the soldier packing
around a small fuel tank (propane?) and having this weird circular
bulge near the stock of the weapon, and an exhaust port somewhere
spitting out hot gases.

- -- 
