    'index' => 'ae409',
    'month' => '07',
    'body' => 'Ethan Henry <ehenry@mag1.magmacom.com> wrote:
> > 5700AD is as far removed from us as we are from those of 1700BC, the bronze
> > age of ancient mesopotamia and Middle Kingdom Egypt.  Spaceflight is as old
> > as iron is to us and London, New York and Moscow are as remote as Nineveh and Ur. 

This is an awfully good point!  One of the things that I didn\'t like about
the New Era is that they seemed to forget about this: 20th century
references abounded, and for no real reason.

Just the sheer volume of history (even assuming that it was all preserved)
and historical data will overwhelm someone who was trying to research it.
Naming US Presidents would be a lot like naming Egyptian or Chinese rulers.

A reference to "Aslan" would be as obscure in the Far Future as a reference
to "Ninkasi" is today (would you drink from an unmarked, opaque container
labelled "Ninkasi"?).

> It will be possible for an average university-graduate type to know 
> a lot about the 20th century, but it probably won\'t be common.
> ("I majored in 20th century history." "ooh, database archaeology, huh?")

Exactly.
"Yah, database archaeology.  Did you know that for most of the 20th century,
 they didn\'t have full-text searching?"
"No way, get outta here, man!  How did they ever find things?"
"Aparrently they didn\'t.  I\'m doing a paper on their early space travel, and
 I saw a footnote about the \'first star wars\' in the late 20th century.  But
 I can\'t find any refernece to it in contemporary military histories."

> Some figures will remain on the tips of everyone\'s tongue. Some names will
> be forever lost.  The average 58th century native Terran will probably know
> that John F. Kennedy was an American president,

And they\'ll probably remember Washington and Lincoln (but I\'ll bet a lot of
people will confuse Kennedy and Lincoln - after all, they were both "the one
that got shot").

Unless someone is _really_ interested in it, the most detail that
anyone will ever go into would probably be like Larry Gonick\'s (excellent)
_A Cartoon History of the Universe_.  There\'s just too much information for
anyone to be more than casually aware of it.

Eris wrote:
> Technology on planets like Earth wouldn\'t fall far enough to loose access
> to their knowledge base...and that raises the question:  Why did the "long
> night" last over a thousand years?

Planets like Earth didn\'t loose their knowledge base - Earth was the core of
the Old Earth Union, a space-faring trading group that lasted through the
Long Night.  It\'s the other, less-optimal worlds that didn\'t fare so well.

Remember, the Long Night was triggered by a currency collapse: interstellar
banks started to refuse to honor notes and drafts on "far away" branches.
It doesn\'t take much of this for trade to become a local (or even
non-existant) thing.  Once trade collapsed, only worlds with a friendly
ecosystem and a population that could be locally supported remained.  These
worlds are fairly few and far between.

The end result being that there was no _point_ to going off-world; many
economies suffered a long depression or stagnation even on the best worlds.
Add to that a number of groups with working starships that decided that the
best way to deal with the financial problems was to take what they wanted
from those less-well-armed, compound it with Fear, Uncertanty, and Doubt,
and pretty soon nobody goes trading anymore.


