    'index' => 'ae414',
    'body' => 'On Thu, 11 Jul 1996, Christopher Sean Hilton wrote:

> Our ability to store information for short periods of time has increased
> by leaps and bounds over the past ten years but noone is thinking of long
> term storage. The lifespan of information on magnetic tape is less than 20
> years and on optical disk it probably less than 100 years. This is without
> regard to data layout and character set encoding which brings up a whole
> other set of issues. So even if a CD-ROM would last until 5700~5800 AD it
> would be difficult to decipher without a contemporary ASCII table and
> printed copy of the CD-ROM data layout books as rosetta stones so to
> speak. I think it\'s foolish to assume that we will employ a significant
> portion of the earth\'s workforce in the endevour of constantly converting
> databases which are meaningless out of context from "obsolete" formats to
> "modern" formats every twenty years or so. 

It depends on what the information is.  A business that coverts to a new 
storage format will transfer all of its current customer database into 
the new format.  Non-current customers\' data will probably not be 
transferred.  So, over the long term, you are correct: none of this 
information is likely to be available very long after the customer\'s 
death. 

But, really, I wasn\'t referring to such "knowledge" at all.  Loosely 
stated, I am referring to the type of information one could find in a 
library.  

Will this sort of information be converted?  I think you\'ll grant that 
the "core" stuff (meaning, the stuff that is most often accessed) will 
be.  There will also be items which, although not frequently used, will 
be determined to have historical importance (that importance, of course, 
being determined in the then-current context, which will undoubtedly 
exclude some items that would be considered VERY relevant 200 or 2000 
years from then) and will therefore also be converted - perhaps by 
privately funded organizations, or even by business-sponsored 
conversion.  

The rest?  Sure, it may fall by the wayside.  It may not be converted, 
and will eventually deteriorate beyond usability.

Nonetheless, the point of my post was that we have HUGE stores of 
knowledge (again, referring to library-type knowledge) in comparison to 
even 200 years ago.  Not only do we have a lot more knowledge stored, we 
also have more copies of that knowledge - and those copies are scattered 
all over, under the care of many different people and organizations.

So, even if we assume that 90% of our knowledge will be wiped out due to 
lack of conversion to subsequent storage methods (something I consider 
highly unlikely, but for the sake of argument I stipulate it), the 
remaining stores will still dwarf what we have of the knowledge base from 
3000 years ago.


- -Joe
