    'body' => 'On Thu, 11 Jul 1996, Leonard Erickson wrote:

> In somewhere mysterious you write:
> 
> > Our ability to store information for short periods of time has increased
> > by leaps and bounds over the past ten years but noone is thinking of long
> > term storage.
> 
> Not entirely true. A lot of archivists, Library type, and even some
> computer science types are quite aware of the problem.
> 
> > The lifespan of information on magnetic tape is less than 20
> > years and on optical disk it probably less than 100 years.
> 
> Computer tapes 20 years old may be hard to read. Cassette tapes that
> old are quite readable. I\'ve got audio tapes that old, and software
> that is approaching that age.
> 

Cassette tapes that old are worse. You can hear the print through on a 
twenty year old cassette as noise in between songs where there was 
originally "silence". 


> > This is without
> > regard to data layout and character set encoding which brings up a whole
> > other set of issues. So even if a CD-ROM would last until 5700~5800 AD it
> > would be difficult to decipher without a contemporary ASCII table and
> > printed copy of the CD-ROM data layout books as rosetta stones so to
> > speak. I think it\'s foolish to assume that we will employ a significant
> > portion of the earth\'s workforce in the endevour of constantly converting
> > databases which are meaningless out of context from "obsolete" formats to
> > "modern" formats every twenty years or so. 
> 
> It doesn\'t take *that* much of the workforce. Plus, there are some
> storage formats being worked on that look to be a lot more stable over
> long periods.

It depends on the storage format of the original material and the 
cost that the vendor of the new information system assigns to data 
conversion. It also depend on whether or not the customer is willing to 
pay the vendor\'s price. This is highly variable. The hospital that I used 
to work for had medical records dating back to 1826. They had on-line 
information dating back to 1987. The online data is simple to convert so 
it stays but the paper information is purged once it\'s confirmed that 
the the patient has died and the info is no longer needed. This is the 
typical case.

> 
> But now you know why businesses are so strong on hardcopy records.
> 

Hardcopy records are _currently_ difficult to save. In many cases they 
are not stored on acid free paper so the storage medium itself is 
degrading (like magnetic tapes).

> Another factor just coming into play are the legal aspects. There are
> court rulings that make such things as email by government employees
> "public records" which must be stored indefinitely.

Don\'t confuse indefinitely with infinitely. You are observing a current
law which is up to the whim of the contemporary court system. A reversal
of the decision that this information must be stored "indefinitely" could
result in it\'s lawful erasure on privacy grounds. And there is only a 
finite amount of time and money that we can spend maintaining this 
information. Eventually someone will deem it useless and toss it into the 
cirular file.

> 
> And folks like Project Gutenberg are working hard to get a lot of stuff
> into machine readable format. And that stuff *will* keep getting moved
> to new formats.

Chris
