    'from' => 'Stewart Eyres spe@astro.keele.ac.uk',
    'body' => 'Hi there

shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) said:

>
>Just off the top of my head, Chamberlain, Churchill, and Thatcher. And
>I *think* the current one is Majors.
>
>As for the royals, there\'s Queen Elizabeth II, Prince Phillip, and Prince
>Andrew (again just off the top of my head). 
>
>Julius, Augustus, Nero, Octavius, Claudius, and I can\'t recall the
>*name* of the one who was so infamous for perversions and debauchery
>(it\'s on the tip of my tongue, it just won\'t come...)

This just proves you are *not* average, which probably holds for
everyone on this list!  The *current* royals are easier, as they are
media targets.  Can you name the royals since say Queen Victoria, or
Henry VIII (please don\'t, I\'m just pointing out that naming them is a
long way from knowing anything about them).  What did Augustus or
Octavius actually do?  The point is that even if such information is
preserved into the 57th century (a debate I *do not* want to get
involved in) almost no one will care enough to learn. and schools will
have more important things to teach!

Someone said "neither will the UK" in response to my point that the
USA didn\'t exist in the 57th century.  I agree, I don\'t even expect
the UK to last long into the 21st century.  This wasn\'t my point - it
was the assumption that all Imperial citizens would know what was
essentially history trivia of some little nation of only 500 million
people, which ceased to exist in any meaningful sense millenia before
- - this, to my mind, showed a certain lack of realisation of quite how
distant the Imperium was from Terra today in terms of both time and
physical scales.  I also agree that references to contempory culture
etc. *do* provide a reference point, but I prefer references that are
seriously warped from reality as we (most of us) see it (a la "Saint
Elvis") - warped by both time and the different perspective of
Imperial citizens.

"Terran history in the 20th century was an ongoing series of
world-wide civil wars, with generals such as Churchill, Stalin, and
Kennedy fighting for control of the United Nations.  Some scholars
have attributed the rise in technology over that period to the
constant need to arm and cope with the consequences of numerous civil
wars, although this view has been discredited by Mattitian
sociopolitical theory.  This period is viewed as the end of the
`Terran Dark Ages\', prior to the `Golden Interstellar Age\' staring in
the 21st Century."

The writings of say Lincoln, or the speaches of Churchill may still
exist, but they will be interpreted in a modern context, and so
certainly not understood as they were at the time.  The writings in
the Bible, which are to some degree an historical account, are not
wholly understandable, and often it appears to contradict itself.  The
problem isn\'t only keeping a faithful record, but also the correct
understanding.

"Government of the People, for the People, by the People".  Did
Strephon really understand this in the same way as we think we do?
His government relied on inherited power, and provided an independence
to the nobility which in no way ensured fair government for his
subjects.  He refused Dulinor\'s democratic reforms (hence the
assasination), and whil he may have been right that the Imperium
wasn\'t ready for, he couldn\'t really believe (as suggested in Survival
Margin) that his empire related to Lincoln\'s view of government.  The
words may be remembers, even the achievements of those who said them,
but the understanding will change.

Stewart Eyres <spe@astro.keele.ac.uk>
