    'body' => '>>Just off the top of my head, Chamberlain, Churchill, and Thatcher.
>>And I *think* the current one is Majors.

Major, not Majors. But close enough for jazz. :)

>Now for some royalty...George I to IV..was there a V?  William, only 1
>really, I think.  Henry, oh my there were a lot of them, I-VIII.  The
>2 Elizabeths, and can\'t forget Victoria.  Mary...was she queen before
>she lost her head, and Mary of William and Mary...but that William
>wasn\'t King..right?  Albert was Prince Consort and so is Phillip.
>Pre-1066, there was Harold and Owen and Authur.  Think Robin
>Hood..Richard I-III.  James I & II.  Charles I-III, wasn\'t it III that
>lost his head...so do we include Cromwell here?  <g> Just how many
>Edwards have there been..7?

Hmm.. okay, yes there was a George V and a George VI.

William I-IV. William I was William the Conqueror, William II was not long
after, Willaim III was William of William and Mary, William IV was just
before Victoria. All being well, Prince William will become William V.
There was also a Stephen not long ofter William I. William I himself beat
Harold. Queen Anne was the daughter of William and Mary.

Lots of Henrys, and Mary was the daughter of Henry VIII (who wasn\'t
beheaded - that was Mary, Queen of Scots, beheaded by Elizabeth I, Henry
VIII\'s other
daughter).

Plenty of Edwards too, VIII of them.

There were 2 Charles, Charles I was beheaded by Cromwell, Charles II
defeated Cromwell\'s bunch and restored the Monarchy. Cromwell could have
become Oliver I had he wanted, but he refused the crown.

There were 3 Richards, the third of whom was beaten by Henry Tudor at Bosworth,
who them became Henry VII.

The James. There were 2 of these, but it gets a bit complicated here. James I
of England was James VI of Scotland, and James II of England was James VII of
Scotland. This also leads to Elizabeth II of England being Elizabeth I of
Scotland. James II was overthrown by William of Orange, who became William III
when he married Mary.

There has never been a historically documented Arthur, and there\'s never likely
to be another one, as every time the heir to the throne has been called
Arthur he\'s died before ascending the throne. As a result, it\'s considered
a very unlucky name for a royal. THE Arthur was probably a Romano-British
war-leader who resisted the invasion of the Saxons. Most of the romantic
legends are probably Breton in origin (Brittany in France being Lesser Britain,
as opposed to Great Britain).

Prince Albert was the only Prince Regent; Prince Phillip is the Duke of
Edinburgh.

Have I missed anyone out? If I have, my apologies, I\'m am engineer, not a
historian. :)

Nik.

