    'date' => 'Mon, 15 Jul 1996 12:26:00  0400',
    'body' => 'ROWAN Iain writes:

>Some people have a problem with the physics of certain things in
>Traveller - I have a huge problem with this.  Three and a half thousand
>years of development, contact with a variety of alien races, intermixing
>with a variety of human races, all with different cultural and historical
>backgrounds - and the predominant culture is \'similar\' to late C20
>America?  Please!  This makes virus look like a well thought out, likely
>and consistent plot development.

   And here we are in the 20th century, some 2000 years later, after
contact (and mixing) with a variety of other human cultures and
races, all with different cultural and historical backgrounds--and yet we
still quote Julius Caesar.  For that matter we still quote Moses, and he
dates back some 3500 years, give or take.

>I never got the impression from CT that this was the case, but it
>certainly seemed to come out in the TNE materials I read, and I think that
>it was one of the weakest parts of the mileu.

   Discounting ``Sneaks and Geeks``, for apparent reasons, the rest of
the TNE material is no more or less riddled with American references
than say, any of the material published from 1982 to 1992.

>The authors of Traveller may well be late C20 Americans, but then the
>majority of SF writers are late C20 Americans, and that doesn\'t stop
>some of them producing believable, interesting yet different far future
>cultures.

   The majority of science-fiction writers produce material that is no more
or less riddled with Anglocentric remarks than Traveller is.  A few, very
good writers have been able to create material that transcends the
limitations placed on us by our background and environment.  The few
very good writers out there do not write for RPGs, at least not for very
long.

>I would suggest that the vast majority of Imperial citizens would have no
>knowledge of the US\' existence.  Why would somebody whose
>ancestors have been living on world x for 2000 years be bothered
>about the early history of one of the nations which was part of UNSCA
>which eventually became the Terran Confederation etc etc.

   They would, for the same reasons that people in the US and Brazil
have knowledge of Ancient Greece or Egypt.  They might not know all
the particulars, and they probably get some very basic facts wrong,
but they would know that there was this thing called the `United States`
or more likely just `America` on Earth a *long* time ago.

   Fortunately or unfortunately, the United States of America is currently
*the* predominate cultural and political power of Earth, has been since
1945, and will continue to be so well into the 21st century.  After that,
how knows?  But try to find a corner of the planet where you can\'t find
a picture of Walt Disney cartoon  character in someone\'s possession.
Or a rock-n-roll recording.  Or American cigarette (probably being used
as a form of currency).  

   Anyway, the US is the Athens of this era.  While we managed to
defeat our version of Sparta (the USSR), and didn\'t engage it in open
warfare (thank God), because of our status, we will be remembered
for many millennia to come.

   The UK?  ``They were a power that pre-dated America by some years,
in fact the original Americans were UK colonists.  Eventually the
Americans revolted and established their own government.  It wasn\'t
until sometime later, after the Americans increased in power and the UK
began to decline, that the Americans and the UK became friends and
allies against a series of tyrannical enemies that arose on Earth during
the chaotic 20th century.``

   If you were a professor at a university in the Third Imperium and one
of your undergrad students gave that as an answer to the above
question, you would be happy he or she knew so much about that
aspect of ancient history.  You further suspect that the student was
of Solomani heritage.

>There probably would be a few specialised historians who would be
>historians of pre-spaceflight Terra.  But not many.

   We could argue over the numbers, but my guess is that there will be
more pre-spaceflight Terran historians than Old Earth Union historians,
if for no other reason that the pre-spaceflight era was just so darn
interesting in comparison.  World Wars, brink of nuclear holocaust and
all that.  On the other hand, I\'m sure that there will be a much larger
number of Sylean/early Third Imperium historians, as their early history
would be of more relevance to modern Imperials.

>The average Imperial historian would be much more interested in the
>history of their world, their subsector,their sector, their Imperium, than
>they would be in that of a pre-spaceflight nation on Terra.

   I don\'t disagree here (as noted above), it\'s just that it would appear
from canon that the people of the Third Imperium have empathy for the
nation-state known as America.  If my explanation isn\'t satisfactory,
then there has to be another besides ``it isn\'t possible``.

Regards,

Harold





