_on_, regular backups and care will presevere it. Librarians look after books,
y\'know, fixing them if they\'re damaged - and if they can\'t they _get another
copy_ and put it on the shelf. Read: retrieve the data volume from deep backup
storage and reinstall in public access area.

Once tech levels reach - oh, say 10, 11 - the library computers and later,
robots, will be able to indent for nice shiny new dataslugs and cheerfully set a
subprocess up to whack all the data from 100-year-old storage onto brannie
media. If said media\'s got better in the interim, so much the better. That\'s
what they\'ll be there for. It\'s not like some employee putting off moving his
archive databases from 5.25" disks to 3.5" until there\'s no 5.25" drives left in
the organization <yeah, I\'ve seen this happen!>. An expert system programmed
with Librarian-3 or better will think of this, in advance, plan for it, and
won\'t get bored doing the copying. As long as local government can support the
machine\'s budget for new and spare parts & media, things will be dandy.

Oh, yah, and off-site (off-planet!) backups, natch.

\'Course, Virus would bugger this nicely, but I don\'t believe in Santa Claus
either :>

HWF

