    'ts-index' => '1996-07-18.ae486',
    'body' => '> Your Fabulous Facial Friend ("hand" computer) can pick up on these. As simple
>as using different squints to "right or left click the mouse" up to rather more
>complicated UI interactions our immersion in present technology prevents
>us >from even guessing.

The \'different squints\' method is quite okay today - eyetracking as a computer
input is what my PhD thesis was about. Just look at an icon to activate it,
none of this keyboard business. Of course there are still problems, but I won\'t
bore you all with a diatribe on them here. :)

>It\'s a swell description and a whizzy piece of SF, but I can\'t help wondering
>two things; with full voice recognition, wouldn\'t it be far more efficient
>simply to talk to it and ask for what you want - and I realy dread to think of
>the sort of system crash you\'d end up with after, say, a violent sneeze... <g>

Interestingly enough, speech therapists are beginning to see a new problem
being refered to them. People are arriving with voice strain due to operating
speech recognition systems. Think of it this way, if you\'re operating a computer
by speech alone, you\'re putting vour voice to under a lot of stress, using it
far more than normal, so it starts to cause problems. And what do you do if
you lose your voice? How do you operate your machine then?

Overall I think that we\'re still likely to have keyboards of some sort, although
not the qwerty design we\'re used to at present. Intelligent predictive
systems will minimise the amount of typing that needs to be done, but the
fingers will still be the main input medium.

Nik

