    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>> >> But now you know why businesses are so strong on hardcopy records.
>> >
>> > Hardcopy records are _currently_ difficult to save. In many cases they 
>> > are not stored on acid free paper so the storage medium itself is 
>> > degrading (like magnetic tapes).
>> 
>> All too true. But businesses count microfilm as "hardcopy". I have a
>> friend whose job used to be microfilming bank records all day long. And
>> this was for a medium size "local" bank.
>
> This is true too but how long does information on microfilm last before 
> it has to put on another media. Will microfilm last 3700 years or will 
> someone have to take the volumes of data that on it and convert it to 
> something else every couple of hundred years.

While I don\'t have a definitive answer, I rather suspect that microfilm
is *at least* as durable as paper, if not more so. Given "reasonable"
storage conditions, the means of degradation I see as most likely are:

1. oxidation (*very* slow, acetate film is damn stable)
2. migration of dye (the "dye" that the film uses may slowly migrate
   over time)
3. adhesion/bonding (the adjacent pieces of film may adhere if kept in
   contact long enough)

I\'m guessing that these would be stable over 500-1000 year periods. And
given that they were incorporated in some deliberate "time capsules", I
suspect that they are thought to be good for even longer.

> Given that it cost $25.00 / square foot for warehouse 
> space (cool and dry to reduce degradation) the business decision is to 
> throw that information away.

Of course, if the data is on microfiche it\'ll take up a *lot* less
space. You get what? 200 pages per fiche?

> It\'s harder to envision this happening to the government and 
> historical information but that\'s because over our lifetime the 
> Government of the United States is a very stable entity and will perceive 
> some value in maintaining its history. Some time after that changes, some 
> time after the U.S. Government goes away by whatever means the 
> details of the history of this regime will be lost.

Barring some *major* disaster, I think that newspapers and magazines
(on microfiche) will survive in the libraries. And given the interest
that sociologists and even anthropologists show in stuff that\'s only a
hundred or so years old, I expect that the data will be converted to
"modern" storage every so often. If only by research assistants to a
person doing his Phd on "sports trends in the United States of America
(19th through 24th cent.)"

> In 3700 years 
> historical scholars will be able to figure out that the United States 
> existed and who the president was in 1963.

They\'ll be able to read Time, Newsweek, The New York Times, The London
Times, etc for the whole of their existence. 

> But this information won\'t be 
> required reading for every Imperial Citizen and it won\'t be the easiest 
> information to find either.

Depends. I rather expect that any of it that has been converted to
"modern" storage will be readily available *if* you care to look.
"Periodicals, Terran, 20th century, nation, ....."

And given the sheer *number* of scholars needing *something* to do
research on, I rather expect that much of the data will be converted to
"modern" storage formats. I also expect that much of the conversion
will have been done by scanning the originals, and then using text
recognition algorithms on the scans. Which could lead to some
interesting errors untill and unless someone *familiar* with the
language of the period compares the scan and the "text" extracted from
it. Ditto for what will happen to images digitized at the wrong
resolution (you would not *believe* what can happen to a halftoned
image if scanned at the "right" wrong resolution)


