    'topic' => 'Duration of information storage',
    'month' => '07',
    'index' => 'ae503',
    'body' => 'Speaking as an archivist...

We were taught that the rough duration of archival-quality microfilm was
300 years or so, if stored in the right conditions.  Acid-free paper will
last for more than a thousand years (we\'ve got paper that old).
Parchment will last longer (we\'ve got books dating back to the 3rd and 4th
centuries AD; no reason it shouldn\'t last a few centuries more).

Modern computer media (disks, etc.) is too new to have much experience
with yet; I suspect that much of it will be gone within a century, if
not within mere decades.  Lack of reading machinery is probably a more
pressing problem (there are _two_ machines in existence today that 
can read the 1960 U.S. census data tapes.)  OTOH, if you made a CD-ROM
out of pure aluminum instead of plastic-and-aluminum it might well
last for centuries, if not millenia.

If you really want long-term storage, though, carve your words in 
granite, or put them on baked clay tablets.  Pottery is virtually
indestructible (OK, it\'ll shatter, but the fragments will stay
around), unless you physically destroy it (as in, grind to 
powder.)  Stone tablets, likewise.  

In the Far Future, this means that the past history of most planets
can be learned by archaeologists up until the point when they
gotinto the Plastic Age...


Tony Z
