    'body' => 'John wrote:
     
     In the old adventure "Expedition to Zhodane", there was 
     a device to "overlay" a false personality over one\'s real one, to move 
     about Zhodani society without appearing "wrong" to the Thought Police. 
     
     So imagine if a player suddenly discovers that their  personality is 
     just such an "overlay", done without their  knowledge, and the 
     auto-probe suddenly clues them in 
     that they\'re not who they think they are. 
     
     But the impressions of the "real" personality are vague, so you have a 
     whole series of adventures based not on "whodunit", but "whoami" as 
     the player tries to recover  their "real" personality. (Providing, of 
     course, that the "real" personality is in fact the *real* personality 
     <G>) 
     
     "Tonight on _It\'s The Mind_...." 
     -- 

Ever since I saw "Total Recall" I\'ve thought that I had to write a RPG 
adventure sometime that explored the issue of "who am I?".  There was a 
Babylon 5 episode recently (well, recently in the UK) where a monk started 
having nightmares about terrible murders.  It turned out that he had 
committed the murders before being caught and having his personality 
suppressed - he now didn\'t *know* he\'d murdered anyone.  Relatives of the 
victims had hired a psionic to break down the memory suppression, so that 
he would realise what terrible crimes he had committed before one of the 
relatives killed him.  After the monk had been killed, the relative that 
did it was also given a mind wipe, and ended up joining the same religious 
order, since they now had a "vacancy".
It was all done much better than I have described, especially the scene  at 
the end of the episode where the Captain (who was friendly with the monk) 
meets the murdering relative after his mind wipe and has to be reminded 
that he was no worse than his friend, the monk.

Of course, I\'ve never gotten round to writing a scenario on this theme, 
though I did write one on "AI" based on ideas from Bladerunner.  Actually, 
it was a fantasy adventure where a magically animated wooden doll was being 
hunted down by its creator to be destroyed, because the "experiment" hadn\'t 
quite worked right.  The players became involved initially to try and stop 
the damage this doll was doing in the market, but ended up with them having 
to decide whether to give up their captive to its creator.

Oops, I\'ve written a bit more than I meant to, but this is one of my 
favourite subjects.

Cheers,
Liam

