    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> To follow up on the recent Guild thread...I\'m re-reading some Andre Norton
> (to be exact, The Zero Stone and Uncharted Stars). Norton also uses Guilds,
> specifically in this book a gemworkers guild (evaluate stones, design
> settings for the stones, cut stones, etc.).
>
> Norton also has three of her other regular galaxy (or human explored space)
> wide organizations: The Patrol (Space or Galactic, I don\'t recall), the Free
> Traders and the Thieves\' Guild.

With the exception of one book ("The Last Planet" aka "Star Rangers" or
some such) the patrol is always "The Patrol". In that book it *may*
have been "the Space Patrol".

Also, it\'s "the Guild", not "the Theives\' Guild". Which gives it a nice
flavor. If someone mentions "*the* guild" with no qualifiers, everybody
knows *exactly* what they are talking about, but it\'s impossible to
*prove* it. :-)

"The Zero Stone" and "Uncharted Stars" also have a good bit of some of
Norton\'s other major "props". Namely the Forerunners, and the
Zacathans. And I think the First-In Scouts make an appearance as well. 

> Any thoughts on how to make the Free Traders a force to compete successfully
> against the Big Boys? Norton implies that they\'ve got a lot of power--maybe
> in the Imperium they would as well--bending the ears of a few influential
> members of Court...holding enough of a economic lock to compete, or being
> helped by the Imperium to ensure some free trade and competition.

Well, in Norton\'s universe the Free Traders are at least loosely
organized (which helps), plus, since they deal with the "frontier"
areas more, they tend to be a *lot* more experienced when it comes to
combat. And they\'ve got better excuses for going armed. 

Add in the fact that the Patrol does *not* approve of the sort of
illegal stunts the corporations would *like* to pull on the Free
Traders, and you have a workable balance of power.

BTW, that book I mentioned ("Star Rangers"/"The Last Planet") would
make a good example of how to write a neat adventure based around the
aftermath of something like the Civil War that ended the Third
Imperium. The basic idea is that a governor how didn\'t want the
detachment of Star Rangers around to get in the way of his plans
ordered them out to re-survey some planets in an area nobody had
visited in centuries. And he sent them out with inadequate spare parts
in an old ship. The story opens as the ship crash lands on a planet.
Later we run into the passengers from a liner that got lost while
trying to avoid the fighting, and refugees from a Patrol base that got
overun in the fighting. All of these get mixed together while they try
to figure out just why the planet seems to keep "bothering" the humans,
and what happened to the high civilization that used to be there.

Heck, given that Norton wrote a book based around D&D and has allowed
some use of her fantasy stuff in RPG\'s, I think that IG might want to
consider asking for permission to do a "Norton Sourcebook" for T4. Her
drives aren\'t *that* different. They even include mention of something
that sounds a lot like misjumps. And the technology is otherwise not
*that* hard to integrate. The races and backgrounds would be a nice
addition as an alternate universe to play in. And it\'d save a lot of
info that may otherwise disappear for good when she dies (I\'m assuming
that she\'d have a fair amount of input).

- -- 
