    'month' => '09',
    'index' => 'ae589',
    'body' => 'Hello there,

My name\'s Glenn and I\'ve managed to stay "clean" for twelve years. No
wasting time on rpg\'s in all that time (well, a relapse or two, just for
old time\'s sake). But, uh-oh... Some of my friends want me to run Traveller
again... I resisted at first but... oh, the temptation... Now I\'ve fallen
completely off the wagon. I went out and bought T4.

A fine book. Excellent Chris Foss reproductions. Dull but readable
typeface. Better organized than the Traveller Book. Too bad somebody didn\'t
proof-read it too closely, but as an editor I know how it is - deadlines
and such.

And the game seems to have been immensely improved while I was away. I
stopped playing after The Traveller Book, so this is my first exposure to
the Task system - seems very cool indeed - and the armor rules make much
better sense this time round. My favourite RPG seems to have just gotten
better.

But there are those nagging inconsistencies in the Imperium universe which
have always bothered me. So this time out I\'m biting the bullet and
developing my own future history and setting. Maybe someday I\'ll dump big
chunks of it onto somebody\'s ftp site, once I\'ve got the bugs worked out.

In the meantime, here\'s a question I haven\'t seen discussed in the XTML
digests I\'ve been skimming in the MPGN Archives... 

What ever happened to radio-spectrum CETI (Communication with
Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence)? You might point out that the Imperium\'s
got FTL X-boats, what do they need with those old, slow radio waves, right?

Well, it\'s clearly a crowded universe, including scatterlings of Old Terra
all over the place; so there must be a HUGE number of other civilizations,
major races and minor, in all that vastness beyond Known Space. The
Imperium\'s been around a long time, off and on; they could certainly be
carrying on centuries-long radio conversations with other species in the
Orion Arm, not to mention the Perseus and Sagittarius arms. Heck, you might
pick up the occassional "We\'re Here!" beacon transmitting from another
galaxy. IF you\'re listening. If you get bored, it wouldn\'t be so difficult
to set up automated listening stations.

Because maybe... just maybe... somebody out there, 90 degrees away around
the Milky Way\'s disc, has discovered the secret of tachyonic travel. Or at
least a Jump-7 drive. Or a really great Taco recipe. And maybe they want to
share...

In the future history I\'m working on, I plan to have a truly galactic,
Saganesque network of radio civilizations, conversing slowly about such
matters.  At the very least, far-flung civilizations might want to trade
data on supernova chain reactions, or galactic plasma jets, or other
galactic "weather hazard" reports. However, I do suspect any tech-17
societies are going to keep their best techno-goodies close to their
chests, partly for advantage in trade with their closer neighbours, but
also to avoid calling too much unwanted military attention to oneself. 

Is this a topic covered by any Imperium material, canonical or otherwise?

Glenn Grant
Traveller Redux

