>The following is (c)1996 Steven Ward.  Please read and comment.
>=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D
>
>Getting the message across.
>
>The X-Boat network in Traveller.
>
>What is it?
>
>The X-Boat network is the main means of sending messages across the vast=20
>Imperium.  It
>was established 624 (Imperial) and covered the entire Imperium in 718=20
>(Imperial).  The
>backbone of the system is a small craft capable of a maximum speed of Jump=
=20
>4.
>Administration of the X-Boat system is the responsibility of the=20
>Communications Office
>division of the Imperial Interstellar Scout Service (IISS).  Although the=
=20
>maximum speed of an
>X-Boat is jump 4, not all jumps are made at that speed.   Because of the=20
>way the network is
>laid out, the average speed a message travels is Jump 2.6.
>
>How it operates.
>The best way to describe this process is to do it as an example.  Say I was=
=20
>staying at Capital
>and I wanted to drop a message of to a close friend of mine on Regina.  I=
=20
>would address it in
>the following fashion:
>*John Smith@Regina/Regina.TASNET.JS584866
>
>So breaking it down, starting with the far left.  The * informs me that=20
>John is a registered
>voter on Regina then his name.  The @ means located at.  Regina is the=20
>system name,
>Regina is the subsector capitol.  The next part TASNET is the computer=20
>system name and
>the last part is his identity on that system followed by his UPP.
>
>Common computer system domains include:
>TASNET:_Traveller\'s Aid Society.
>EDUNET:_Educational.
>GOVNET:_Local government.
>IMPGOV:_Imperial government.
>COMNET:_Commercial businesses.
>PRIVNET:_Non business.
>
>These are the main ones.  Major corporations\' names are added after the=20
>network name and
>before  the user ID.
>
>I record my message to John using my terminal in my room.  I have the=20
>option of Video,
>Audio, or text.  The only difference in them is the quality and cost. =20
>Video is 30 credits for
>each ten minutes per jump, audio 10 credits for ten minutes and text one=20
>credit for ten pages.
>Mixed text and pictures\' costs one credit per page.  If I was not using a=
=20
>terminal in my room,
>there are public terminals located in most starports.  Although video=20
>transmissions are only
>available on class A starports, audio class B and C or less is text only.
>Billing is in Imperial credits and worked out with the jump speed of 2.5. =
=20
>If he was not on the
>main route, the message would be passed to the Imperial Courier Service=20
>(ICS) for final
>delivery.
>
>I have finished my message and instruct the terminal to send.  The terminal=
=20
>then gives me
>the option to have my message encrypted, this doubles the cost of the=20
>message.  From here,
>the data is compressed and passed to the local communications system for=20
>transmission to
>an X-Boat station or passed to the ICS for delivery onto an X-Boat route.
>
>An X-Boat drops into realspace.  The pilot then activates the recovery=20
>beacon and aligns the
>communications array to the X-Boat station.  An X-Boat station is=20
>constructed close to entry
>points of Hyperspace and contains fuel, pilot stations and communications=
=20
>arrays.  The
>station dispatches an X-Boat Tender with a fresh pilot and fuel.  Once it=
=20
>has reached the
>boat, it recovers it, changes crew and refuels it.  This process takes=20
>about four hours.  The
>record for this routine is seven minutes.  A single tender can deal with up=
=20
>to six X-Boats at a
>time.  In busy systems, many tenders can be seen working at once to keep=20
>the network
>going.  Once re-fuelled and a new pilot aboard, the X-boat is released and=
=20
>gets ready to
>jump.  While all this activity is going on, the X-Boat is still getting=20
>data and messages.=7F
>
>Once all checks are finished aboard the pilot shuts down the communication=
=20
>array and
>departs the system.  The pilot from the X-Boat is given another job,=20
>whether this be aboard
>the tender or at the X-Boat station.  After a week in normal space he is=20
>reassigned to another
>X-Boat and his job starts again.
>
>What is the ICS?
>
>The ICS maintains a fleet of type S scout/couriers.  It is they who take=20
>the messages to
>systems off the main network.  They are mostly modified with the passenger=
=20
>compartments
>removed and replaced with extra computer storage and extra fuel tankage. =
=20
>They depart at
>different speeds taking their messages to wherever they need to go.
>
>How do I collect my mail?
>Usually this is just  case of connecting up to the planet\'s data net and=20
>accessing it that way.
>If you are on the move, this can be tricky.  Copies of mail are held at=20
>subsector and sector
>capitals and at TAS hostels.  The last option only applies if you are a=20
>member of TAS.  Mail
>is also archived at scout bases, this option requires an administration fee=
=20
>of about 100 credits
>and a week to accomplish.  You also need to produce proof of identity.  A=
=20
>standard Imperial
>bank card is usually all that is required.
>
>What else does the X-Boat system handle?
>You can make bank payments at an X-Boat office.   The information is=20
>encoded and then
>sent to the back of your choice.  This has become a standard way of paying=
=20
>for starships.
>
>Does the X-Boat carry military transmissions?
>Yes, unless the transmissions are secure.  If they are secure then the=20
>Imperial agency
>sending the transmissions uses an Imperial courier vessel.  Imperial=20
>courier ships are rated
>at Jump 4 with a few being capable of Jump 6!
>
>
>What about parcels or paper transmissions?
>To some, a letter is the ultimate secure transmission.  You cannot drop a=
=20
>letter into a
>computer and scan for a phrase.  Someone has to read it all the way=20
>through.  Letters are
>handled by the ICS except they are not X-Boat sent.  Instead the message is=
=20
>accepted at the
>ICS office and then passed on with other letters and parcels to a cargo=20
>ship.  Letter post
>costs one credit per 100grams of weight.  Parcels on the other hand can=20
>make licensed
>carriers a tidy profit.  For ease of packing aboard ships, parcels must be=
=20
>sent using a
>standard design.  The boxes are available at starports everywhere at the=20
>cheap price of a
>tenth of its size in credits..  The smallest box is a 10cm plastic cube and=
=20
>this costs one credit.
>The postage for this item is 5 credits.  A cubic metre costs ten credits=20
>and postage costs 500.
>The formula used to calculate this is: (size*size*size)/6*10.  Size=3D size=
=20
>in cms.  So the metre
>box is 100*100*100 =3D300/6=3D50*10=3D500.  Postage is charged per 2 jumps=
 or=20
>fraction thereof.
>The parcels are collected and dropped into a cargo container for a sector.
>So, I decide to send John a litre of water.  The water fits into a metre=20
>cube and I take it to the
>ICS office.  There I pay my 2500 credits for it to be carried 24 parsecs. =
=20
>The package is
>loaded into a cargo container along with nine other metre cubes for Regina.=
=20
> Each cargo
>container will hold ten cubic metres for each ton of displacement.  Once=20
>loaded, a licensed
>trader is contacted for delivery.
>
>Note:  Since the ICS has limited ships available, they rely upon licensed=
=20
>carriers.  Obtaining
>a licence is not easy. First an application form has to be filled out and a=
=20
>fee of 500,000
>credits is paid.  Then the applicant is given a thorough background check=
=20
>if anything looks
>suspect then their application is refused and the fee is kept.  If all=20
>looks good, the applicant is
>granted a licence.
>
>ICS regulations prevent more than five tons of a ships\' cargo space from=20
>being used for mail.
>This prevents unscrupulous captains from running off with mail and also=20
>means there is a
>steady flow of carriers.  Each ton of space nets the carrier 5000 credits.
>
>If a group of governments is pitching together for a Subsidised Merchant=20
>and the ICS thinks it
>will suit their needs then they will throw in one fifth of the cash for it.=
=20
> The merchant is usually
>given first pick of the cargo.
>
>The cargo is then transported to its destination in its pod.  It may along=
=20
>the way make stops
>to drop off mail pods and collect more.
>
>MegaTraveller.
>The X-Boat system operates at full capacity until about 1120.  Once fleets=
=20
>start to diminish,
>many systems start to lose contact.  The Aslan\'s hold off attacking X-Boats=
=20
>because they
>present no threat.  Many ships and pilots where lost in systems that had=20
>major battles as they
>became easy targets for stray missiles.  Once the virus starts to rampage=
=20
>through Imperial
>space many X-Boats become infected.  They become carriers of the Virus. =20
>Since they
>contain only enough fuel for a jump 4 they drift aimlessly.  It is during=
=20
>the rebellion the ICS
>makes the bold decision not to spy on enemy systems.  This leads to Lucan\'s=
=20
>and Dulinor\'s
>fleets to intentionally destroy X-Boats in enemy territory.  Vagr pirates=
=20
>prey on them for
>spares and the long range jump drives.
>
>New Era.
>There is not the personnel to maintain something as complex as a network of=
=20
>ships.  A vague
>communications network exists but it lacks the range of the old X-Boats. =
=20
>Many have been
>found in systems, dead and lifeless.  They are boarded and scavenged for=20
>spares.  Since
>they have no manoeuvre drive the hulls are just left to decay.  No X-Boat=
=20
>ever became a
>Vampire ship simply because they could not refuel.
>
>References:
>I took and based my information on the following sources.
>Book 6 Scouts.
>Imperial Encyclopaedia.
>Supplement 7 Traders and Gunboats.
>
>Authors\' notes:
>
>Well, I finally did it.  I always thought it would be a bit longer than=20
>what I have here!
>I hope that this will provide inspiration for all players out there.  I can=
=20
>be contacted at:
>Steven.Ward@Brunel.ac.uk
>
>
>----
>Stephen? It\'s been 15 hours. We are gonna grow old and die in here.=20
>Stephen? Stephen, there\'s a Martian war machine parked outside.=20
>They\'d like to have a word with you about the common cold."=20
>-- Vance Hendricks to Dr. Franklin in Babylon 5:"Infection"
>
>Steven Ward
>E-Mail: Steven.Ward@Brunel.ac.uk=20
>World wide web: http://www.wlihe.ac.uk/~ward/
