    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> I\'m not very clear on how sand casters were ment to be used during book
> three combat?  Is the sand shot in space to form a shield or is it shot at
> an enemy target to protect against their shots?

Shot into space around your ship.

> There is some mention of moving sand during the Movement Phase and there is
> a defensive DM of -3 for every 25mm of sand an enemy shot has to go through.
> But what is the area of effect for a single sand shot?  Also, if a ship
> travels through a field of sand does it take damage?

I think that sand covered the hex your ship was in when you fired it.
And it kept moving with the vector your ship had when you fired it.
Thus if you manuevered, you\'d leave the sand cloud behind, following
your old course. Note that "manuevering" includes accelerating in the
same direction..

I don\'t think they assumed a ship wouldn\'t take damage, but to be
realistic, I\'d say that it depends on how fast the ship is moving.
Obviously, sand can\'t damage your ship, so that means that moving thru
it at a relative velocity of 6 (ie doing a 6 g burn to get out of the
cloud you\'ve released) has to be harmless. For anything faster, there
should be damage. How much is a good question.

Note that a lot of the above is based on the Mayday rules, which made
things a bit clearer.

- -- 
